# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel] The American National Standards Institute–Nanotechnology Standards Panel (ANSI-NSP) enables stakeholders in nanotechnology to work together to coordinate the development of voluntary standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel] Such standards include terminology and materials properties and measurement procedures to facilitate commercialization of applications and uses of nanotechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel] ANSI established the panel in August 2004, and membership is open to all parties interested in nanotechnology standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel] By 2018, the group was recognized as one of "promoters of Nanotechnology." The organization appears in the usual directories of internationally recognized nanotechnology organizations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel] ANSI leaders participates in academic conferences, including at Pharmaceutics 2022 in Dubai, and in 2024 at Purdue University.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Founded in the early 18th century as a pearling and fishing settlement, Dubai became a regional trade hub in the 20th century after declaring itself a free port (1901) and extending the Creek (1961).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Modest oil revenue helped accelerate Dubai's development from the 1960s to the 1990s, when the city started to diversify its economy.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 2018, oil production contributed less than 1% to the emirate's GDP.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Rapid construction since the 1990s has produced one of the world's densest skylines, including the world's tallest building, the Burj Khalifa.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Extensive land-reclamation projects have added more than 300 kilometres (190 mi) of artificial coastline.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The city has a large real estate market, especially in the luxury segment.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai's economy centres on trade, tourism, aviation, financial services, and real estate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Dubai International Financial Centre (DIFC) is one of the world's major financial centres.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 2024, Dubai was the seventh most-visited city globally.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai International Airport (DXB) is the world's busiest airport for international passenger traffic, handling over 92 million passengers in 2024.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Many theories have been proposed about the origin of the word "Dubai".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] One theory suggests the word used to be the *souq* in Ba.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The linguist Zana Vahidzadeh (Dana Pishdar) holds that the word comes from 'money', a reference to the prosperity of the trading centre or that the word refers to 'two brothers'—Deira and Bur Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The poet and scholar Ahmad Mohammad Obaid traces it to the same word, but to its alternative meaning of "baby locust" (جراد) due to the abundance of locusts in the area before settlement.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The history of human settlement in the area now defined as the United Arab Emirates is complex and extensive, formed by the extensive trading links between the civilisations of the Indus Valley and Mesopotamia, and even by cultures as far afield as the Levant.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Archaeological finds in the emirate of Dubai, particularly at Al-Ashoosh, Al Sufouh, and the notably rich trove from Saruq Al Hadid show settlement through the Ubaid and Hafit periods, the Umm Al Nar and Wadi Suq periods, and the three Iron Ages in the UAE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The area was known to the Sumerians as Magan and was a source of metallic goods, notably copper and bronze.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The area was covered with sand about 5,000 years ago as the coast retreated inland, becoming part of the city's present coastline.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Pre-Islamic ceramics have been discovered from the 3rd and 4th centuries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Before the introduction of Islam to the area, people in this region worshiped *Bajir* (or *Bajar*).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] After the spread of Islam in the region, the Umayyad Caliph of the eastern Islamic world conquered southeast Arabia and drove out the Sassanians.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Excavations by the Dubai Museum in the region of *Al-Jumayra* (Jumeirah) found several artefacts from the Umayyad period.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] An early mention of Dubai in 1095 is in the *Book of Geography* by the Andalusian-Arab geographer Abu Abdullah al-Bakri.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Venetian pearl merchant Gasparo Balbi visited the area in 1580 and mentioned Dubai (as *Dibei*) for its pearling industry.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai is thought to have been established as a pearling and fishing village in the early 18th century and was, by 1822, a town of some 700–800 members of the Bani Yas tribe and subject to the rule of Sheikh Tahnun bin Shakhbut of Abu Dhabi.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1822, a British naval surveyor noted that Dubai was at that time populated by a thousand people living in an oval-shaped town surrounded by a mud wall, scattered with goats and camels.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The main footpath out of the village led to a reedy creek, while another trailed off into the desert and merged into caravan routes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1833, after tribal feuds, members of the Al Bu Falasah tribe seceded from Abu Dhabi and established themselves in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The exodus from Abu Dhabi was led by Obeid bin Saeed and Maktoum bin Butti, who became joint leaders of Dubai until Ubaid died in 1836, leaving Maktoum to establish the Maktoum dynasty.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai signed the General Maritime Treaty of 1820 with the British government along with other Trucial States, following the British campaign in 1819 against Ras Al Khaimah.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] This led to the 1853 Perpetual Maritime Truce.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai—like its neighbours on the Trucial Coast—entered into an exclusivity agreement in which the United Kingdom took responsibility for the emirate's security in 1892.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1841, a smallpox epidemic broke out in Bur Dubai, forcing residents to relocate east to Deira.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1896, fire broke out in Dubai, a disastrous occurrence in a town where many family homes were still constructed from *barasti* (palm fronds).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The conflagration consumed half of Bur Dubai's houses, and the Deira district was said to have been destroyed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] An enslaved woman was caught in the act of starting one such blaze and was put to death.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1901, Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum established Dubai as a free port with no taxation on imports or exports, and also gave merchants parcels of land and guarantees of protection and tolerance.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] These policies led merchants not only to move directly from Lingeh, but also from those who had settled in Ras Al Khaimah and Sharjah (which had historical links with Lingeh through the Al Qawasim tribe) to Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] An indicator of the growing importance of the port of Dubai is the movements of the steamer of the Bombay and Persia Steam Navigation Company, which from 1899 to 1901 paid five visits annually to Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1902, the company's vessels made 21 visits to Dubai, and from 1904 on, the steamers called fortnightly, trading 70,000 tons of cargo in 1906.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The frequency of these vessels only accelerated Dubai's role as an emerging port and trading hub of preference.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Lorimer notes the transfer from Lingeh "bids fair to become complete and permanent", and also that the town had by 1906 supplanted Lingeh as the chief entrepôt of the Trucial States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The "Great Storm" of 1908 struck the pearling boats of Dubai and the coastal emirates towards the end of the pearling season that year, resulting in the loss of a dozen boats and over 100 men.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The disaster was a major setback for Dubai, with many families losing their breadwinners and merchants facing financial ruin.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] These losses came at a time when the tribes of the interior were also experiencing poverty.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1910, in the Hyacinth incident, the town was bombarded by HMS *Hyacinth*, with 37 people killed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] As well as expanding its regional trade links, Dubai was also an important regional centre for the collection, sale, and trade of pearls.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The collapse of the pearling industry plunged the city into a deep depression, and many residents lived in poverty or migrated to other parts of the Persian Gulf.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1937, an oil exploration contract was signed, guaranteeing royalty rights for Dubai and concessionary payments to Sheikh Saeed bin Maktoum.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] But due to World War II, oil was not struck until 1966.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In its early days, Dubai was constantly at odds with Abu Dhabi.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1947, a border dispute between Dubai and Abu Dhabi on the northern sector of their border escalated into war.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Arbitration by the British government resulted in a cessation of hostilities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Despite a lack of oil, Dubai's ruler from 1958, Sheikh Rashid bin Saeed Al Maktoum, used revenue from trading activities to build infrastructure, initially through loans raised from local merchants and the ruler of Kuwait.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Private companies were established to build and operate infrastructure, including electricity, telephone services, and both the ports and airport operators.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] An airport of sorts (a runway built on salt flats) was established in Dubai in the 1950s and in 1959, the emirate's first hotel, the Airlines Hotel, was constructed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] This was followed by the Ambassador and Carlton Hotels in 1968.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Throughout the late 1950s, the British had urged Sheikh Rashid to approve a town plan to manage an already burgeoning real estate market.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1959, through the correspondence of the British political agent, Sheikh Rashid invited architect John Harris to Dubai to discuss the parameters of a town plan.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In May 1960, Harris returned to Dubai with the plan.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Harris, who ran his own architectural practice, had only a matter of weeks to create the plan after receiving aerial photographs of the city that spring.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] No later than 1961, the British engineering firm Halcrow was marking the city's street system as shown on the plan and hardening designated routes with asphalt.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The plan continued to function as a guide for further extensions of Dubai's street system as municipal funding became available.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Harris's plan made only minimal proposals to disrupt the commercial and social life in the existing areas of Bur Dubai and Deira.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Therefore, new development was proposed outside these areas, further inland from the Gulf.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] While the town plan of 1960 envisioned a very low-rise city that was not realised, its proposed road system was largely implemented as planned.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Harris's firm acted independently of Halcrow, but the plan's accurate representation of ongoing land reclamation and the future Maktoum Bridge, which had not yet been proposed to the municipality, suggests that the two firms kept an open line of communication.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The master plan's road system also served as a guide for the municipality in designating utility easements, as these became increasingly necessary.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1959, Dubai's first telephone company was established, with 51% owned by IAL (International Aeradio Ltd) and 49% by Sheikh Rashid and local businesspeople.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1961, both the electricity and telephone companies rolled out operational networks.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The water company (Rashid was chairman and majority shareholder) constructed a pipeline from wells at Awir and a series of storage tanks and, by 1968, Dubai had a reliable supply of piped water.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The same year, a sand tax was briefly imposed by Rashid in an effort to boost trade by monetising the Emirate's most abundant resource.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The tax was lifted after 11 days, making it the shortest-lived tax in the region's history.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] On 7 April 1961, the Dubai-based MV *Dara*, a five-thousand-ton British-flagged vessel that plied the route between Basra (Iraq), Kuwait, and Bombay (Mumbai, India), was caught in unusually high winds off Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Early the next morning, in heavy seas off Umm al-Quwain, an explosion tore out the second-class cabins and started fires.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The captain gave the order to abandon ship, but two lifeboats capsized, and a second explosion occurred.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] A flotilla of small boats from Dubai, Sharjah, Ajman, and Umm al-Quwain picked up survivors, but 238 of the 819 persons on board were lost in the disaster.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Construction of Dubai's first airport began on the northern edge of the town in 1959, and the terminal building opened for business in September 1960.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The airport was initially serviced by Gulf Aviation (flying Dakotas, Herons, and Viscounts) but Iran Air commenced services to Shiraz in 1961.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1962, the British Political Agent noted that "Many new houses and blocks of offices and flats are being built... the Ruler is determined, against advice [from the British authorities] to press on with the construction of a jet airport...
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1962, with expenditure on infrastructure projects already approaching levels some thought imprudent, Sheikh Rashid approached his brother-in-law, the Ruler of Qatar, for a loan to build the first bridge crossing Dubai Creek.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] This crossing was completed in May 1963 and was paid for by a toll levied on traffic from the Dubai side of the creek to Deira.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] BOAC was initially reluctant to launch regular flights between Bombay and Dubai, fearing insufficient seat demand.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] However, by the time the asphalt runway of Dubai Airport was constructed in 1965, opening Dubai to both regional and long-haul traffic, several foreign airlines were competing for landing rights.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1970, a new airport terminal building was constructed, which included Dubai's first duty-free shops.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Throughout the 1960s, Dubai was the centre of a lively gold trade, with 1968 imports of gold at some £56 million.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] This gold was, in the vast majority, re-exported – mainly to customers who took delivery in international waters off India.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The import of gold to India had been banned, and so the trade was characterised as smuggling.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] However, Dubai's merchants were quick to point out that they were making legal gold deliveries and that it was up to the customer where they took it.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1966, more gold was shipped from London to Dubai than from almost anywhere else in the world (only France and Switzerland shipped more), totaling 4 million ounces.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai also took delivery of over $15 million worth of watches and over 5 million ounces of silver.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The 1967 price of gold was $35 an ounce, but its market price in India was $68 an ounce – a healthy markup.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Estimates at the time put the volume of gold imports from Dubai to India at around 75% of the total market.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] After years of exploration following large finds in neighbouring Abu Dhabi, oil was eventually discovered in territorial waters off Dubai in 1966, albeit in far smaller quantities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The first field was named "Fateh" or "good fortune".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] This accelerated Sheikh Rashid's infrastructure development plans and triggered a construction boom, resulting in a massive influx of foreign workers, primarily from Asia and the Middle East.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Between 1968 and 1975, the city's population grew by over 300%.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] These were constructed by the Chicago Bridge & Iron Company, which gave the beach its local name (Chicago Beach), which was transferred to the Chicago Beach Hotel, which was demolished and replaced by the Jumeirah Beach Hotel in the late 1990s.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Kazzans were an innovative oil storage solution which meant supertankers could moor offshore even in bad weather and avoided the need to pipe oil onshore from Fateh, which is some 60 miles out to sea.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai had already embarked on a period of infrastructural development and expansion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Oil revenue, flowing from 1969 onwards, supported a period of growth, with Sheikh Rashid embarking on a policy of infrastructure development and economic diversification before the emirate's limited reserves were depleted.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Oil accounted for 24% of GDP in 1990 but had fallen to 7% of GDP by 2004.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Critically, one of the first major projects Sheikh Rashid embarked upon when oil revenue began to flow was the construction of Port Rashid, a deep-water free port built by the British company Halcrow.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Originally intended to be a four-berth port, it was extended to sixteen berths during construction.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The project was an outstanding success, with shipping queuing to access the new facilities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The port was inaugurated on 5 October 1972, although its berths were put to use as soon as they were built.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Port Rashid was to be expanded in 1975 by 35 berths before the larger Jebel Ali port was constructed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Port Rashid was the first of a swath of projects designed to create a modern trading infrastructure, including roads, bridges, schools, and hospitals.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai and the other "Trucial States" had long been a British protectorate where the British government took care of foreign policy and defence, as well as arbitrating between the rulers of the Eastern Gulf, the result of a treaty signed in 1892 named the "Exclusive Agreement".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] This was to change with Prime Minister Harold Wilson's announcement, on 16 January 1968, that all British troops were to be withdrawn from "East of Aden".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The decision was to pitch the coastal emirates, together with Qatar and Bahrain, into fevered negotiations to fill the political vacuum left by the British withdrawal.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The principle of union was first agreed upon between the ruler of Abu Dhabi, Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, and Sheikh Rashid of Dubai on 18 February 1968, at a meeting in an encampment at Argoub Al Sedirah, near Al Semeih, a desert stop between the two emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The two agreed to work towards bringing the other emirates, including Qatar and Bahrain, into the union.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Over the next two years, negotiations and meetings of the rulers followed—often stormy—as a form of union was thrashed out.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The nine-state union never recovered from the October 1969 meeting, when British intervention against aggressive actions by two of the Emirates prompted walkouts by Bahrain and Qatar.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] They dropped out of talks, leaving six of the seven "trucial" emirates to agree on a union on 18 July 1971.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] On 2 December 1971, Dubai, together with Abu Dhabi, Sharjah, Ajman, Umm al-Quwain, and Fujairah, joined in the Act of Union to form the United Arab Emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The seventh emirate, Ras Al Khaimah, joined the UAE on 10 February 1972, following Iran's annexation of the RAK-claimed Tunbs islands.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1973, Dubai, along with the other emirates, adopted a uniform currency: the UAE dirham.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In that same year, the prior monetary union with Qatar was dissolved, and the UAE dirham was introduced throughout the Emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Throughout the 1970s, Dubai experienced continued growth fuelled by oil and trade revenues, even as the city witnessed an influx of immigrants fleeing the Lebanese civil war.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Border disputes between the emirates persisted even after the formation of the UAE; it was only in 1979 that a formal compromise was reached, putting an end to disagreements.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 1979, the establishment of the Jebel Ali port, a deep-water port accommodating larger ships, marked a significant development.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Initially facing challenges, Sheikh Mohammed established JAFZA (Jebel Ali Free Zone) around the port in 1985, facilitating the unrestricted import of labour and the export of capital for foreign companies.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Simultaneously, Dubai airport and the aviation industry continued their expansion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Gulf War in early 1991 had a negative financial impact on the city, as depositors and traders withdrew funds and halted trading.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] But Dubai rebounded in a changing political climate and prospered.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In the late 1990s, various foreign trading communities—initially from Kuwait during the Gulf War and later from Bahrain amid the Shia unrest—relocated to Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai served as a refuelling base for allied forces at the Jebel Ali Free Zone during the Gulf War and again during the 2003 Invasion of Iraq.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Subsequent significant increases in oil prices prompted Dubai to maintain its focus on free trade and tourism.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In the early 2000s, construction of artificial islands off Dubai's coast, known as the Palm Islands and The World Islands, began.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Burj Khalifa opened in Dubai in 2010, surpassing the Taipei 101 to become the tallest skyscraper in the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai's smart city initiatives, including smart tourism, play a key role in advancing the city's growth ambitions, primarily through the Smart Dubai project.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 2016, the world's first functioning 3D-printed office building was opened in Dubai, having taken 17 days to build.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Its architect, Killa Design, was the same architect that designed the Museum of the Future.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The construction of Dubai Frame, a 150-meter marvel, commenced in 2014, and was completed in 2017.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] During heightened tensions in the Middle East in the 2020s, Dubai's proximity to regional conflict zones led to frequent flight cancellations and heightened security concerns.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In retaliation for a series of joint Israeli-American strikes on Iran on 28 February 2026, parts of the city were bombarded by Iranian strikes, including the Fairmont The Palm hotel and the municipal airport.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai is on the Persian Gulf coast of the United Arab Emirates and roughly at sea level (16 m or 52 ft above).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The emirate of Dubai borders Abu Dhabi to the south, Sharjah to the northeast, and the Sultanate of Oman to the southeast.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Hatta, a minor exclave of the emirate, is surrounded on three sides by Oman and by the emirates of Ajman (in the west) and Ras Al Khaimah (in the north).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Persian Gulf borders the western coast of the emirate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai lies directly in the Arabian Desert.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Still, its topography differs significantly from that of the southern UAE, with much of Dubai's landscape characterized by sandy desert patterns.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In contrast, gravel deserts dominate much of the country's south.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The sand consists mostly of crushed shells and coral and is fine, clean, and white.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] East of the city, the salt-crusted coastal plains, known as *sabkha*, give way to a north–south running line of dunes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Farther east, the dunes grow larger and are tinged red with iron oxide.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The flat sandy desert gives way to the Western Hajar Mountains, which run alongside Dubai's border with Oman at Hatta.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Western Hajar chain has an arid, jagged, and shattered landscape, whose mountains rise to about 1,300 metres (4,265 feet) in some places.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai has no natural rivers or oases, but it does have a natural inlet, Dubai Creek, which has been dredged to allow large vessels to pass.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai also has multiple gorges and waterholes dotting the base of the Western Al Hajar mountains.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] A vast sea of dunes covers much of southern Dubai and leads into the desert known as The Empty Quarter.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Seismically, Dubai is in a very stable zone—the nearest seismic fault line, the Zagros Fault, is 200 kilometres (124 miles) from the UAE and unlikely to affect Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Experts also say the probability of a tsunami in the region is minimal because the Persian Gulf waters are not deep enough to trigger one.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The sandy desert surrounding the city supports wild grasses and occasional date palms.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Desert hyacinths grow in the *sabkha* plains east of the city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In contrast, acacia and ghaf trees grow in the flat plains within the proximity of the Western Al Hajar mountains.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Several Indigenous trees, such as the date palm and neem, as well as imported trees, such as the eucalyptus and jacaranda, grow in Dubai's natural parks.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The MacQueen's bustard, striped hyena, caracal, desert fox, falcon, and Arabian oryx are common in Dubai's desert.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai is on the migration path between Europe, Asia, and Africa, and more than 320 migratory bird species pass through it in spring and autumn.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The waters of Dubai are home to more than 300 fish species, including the hammour.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Marine life off the coast of Dubai includes tropical fish, jellyfish, coral, dugong, dolphins, whales, and sharks.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Various types of turtles are also found in the area, including the hawksbill turtle and green turtle, which are listed as endangered species.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai features a hot desert climate (Köppen BWh).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Summers are extremely hot, prolonged, windy, and humid, with an average high around 40 °C (104 °F) and overnight lows around 30 °C (86 °F) in the hottest month, August.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Most days are sunny throughout the year.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Winters are mild to warm, with an average high of 24 °C (75 °F) and overnight lows of 14 °C (57 °F) in January, the coolest month.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai summers are also known for very high humidity, which can make them uncomfortable for many, with exceptionally high dew points that can exceed 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Heat index values can reach over 60 °C (140 °F) at the height of summer.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The highest recorded temperature in Dubai is 49.0 °C (120.2 °F).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Very dry, Dubai's average annual precipitation is 79.2 mm (3.12 in).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] But precipitation has been increasing over the last few decades, with annual precipitation reaching 110.7 mm (4.36 in).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Record-setting flooding inundated Dubai in April 2024, demonstrating a lack of appropriate drainage to deal with the immense challenges precipitated by climate change.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai has been ruled by the Al Maktoum family since 1833; the emirate is an absolute monarchy.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai citizens participate in the electoral college to vote representatives to the Federal National Council of the UAE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The ruler, Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum, is also the vice-president and Prime Minister of the United Arab Emirates and a member of the Supreme Council of the Union (SCU).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai appoints eight members to the Federal National Council (FNC) of the UAE, the supreme federal legislative body, for two-term periods.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Dubai Municipality (DM) was established by the then ruler of Dubai, Rashid bin Saeed Al Maktoum, in 1954 for purposes of city planning, citizen services, and upkeep of local facilities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] It has since then evolved into an autonomous subnational authority, collectively known as the Government of Dubai, which is responsible for both the city of Dubai and the greater emirate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Government of Dubai has over 58 governmental departments responsible for security, economic policy, education, transportation, immigration, and is one of only three emirates to have a separate judicial system independent from the federal judiciary of the UAE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Although no legislative assembly exists, the traditional open majlis (council), where citizens and representatives of the Ruler meet, is often used for feedback on certain domestic issues.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] As of September 2019, the population is 3,331,420 –an annual increase of 177,020 people, which represents a growth rate of 5.64%.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The population density is 408.18/km2 –more than eight times that of the entire country.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai is the second-most-expensive city in the region and the 20th-most-expensive city in the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] As of 2013, only about 15% of the emirate's population was made up of UAE nationals, with the rest comprising expatriates, many of whom either have been in the country for generations or were born in the UAE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Approximately 85% of the expatriate population (and 71% of the emirate's total population) was Asian, chiefly Indian (51%) and Pakistani (16%); other significant Asian groups include Bangladeshis (9%) and Filipinos (3%).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] A quarter of the population (local and foreign) reportedly traces their origins to Iran.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In addition, 16% of the population (or 288,000 persons) living in collective labour accommodation were not identified by ethnicity or nationality, but were thought to be primarily Asian.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Some 461,000 Westerners live in the United Arab Emirates, making up 5.1% of its total population.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] There are over 100,000 British expatriates in Dubai, by far the largest group of Western expatriates in the city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The median age in the emirate was about 27 years.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 2014, there were estimated to be 15.54 births and 1.99 deaths per 1,000 people.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] There are other Arab nationals, including GCC nationals.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Arabic is the national and official language of the UAE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Gulf dialect of Arabic is spoken natively by most Emiratis; some Emiratis also speak Shihhi Arabic.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Other major languages spoken in Dubai due to immigration are Malayalam, Sindhi, Gujarati, Urdu, Persian, Hindi, Tamil, Punjabi, Pashto, Bengali, Balochi, Tulu, Kannada, Sinhala, Marathi, Telugu, Tagalog, and Chinese, in addition to many others.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Article 7 of the UAE's Provisional Constitution declares Islam the official state religion of the UAE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The government subsidises almost 95% of mosques and employs all Imams; approximately 5% of mosques are entirely private, and several large mosques have large private endowments.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] All mosques in Dubai are managed by the Islamic Affairs and Charitable Activities Department, also known as "Awqaf", under the Government of Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Constitution of the United Arab Emirates provides for freedom of religion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Expats held to be preaching religious hatred or promoting religious extremism are usually jailed and deported.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Dubai has large Christian, Hindu, Sikh, Baháʼí, Buddhist, Jain and other religious communities residing in the city, as well as a small but growing Jewish community.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] In 2014, more than 56% of Dubai residents were Muslims, while 25% were Christians, 16% were Hindus, and around 2% were adherent of other religions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The Churches Complex in Jebel Ali Village is an area for several churches and temples of different religious denominations, especially Christian denominations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] The largest Christian parish in the world is that of St Mary's Catholic Church in Dubai, owing to the large number of migrant workers in the city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Non-Muslim groups may own houses of worship where they can practice their religion freely, provided they obtain a land grant and permission to build a compound.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Groups that do not have their own buildings may use facilities provided by other religious organisations or worship in private homes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Non-Muslim religious groups are also permitted to advertise group functions openly and distribute various religious literature.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] Catholics are served pastorally by the Apostolic Vicariate of Southern Arabia.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] British preacher Reverend Andrew Thompson claimed that the United Arab Emirates is one of the most tolerant places in the world towards Christians and that it is easier to be a Christian in the UAE than in the UK.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] On 5 April 2020, the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints announced the building of one of their temples in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p01] As part of the announcement, church President Russell M.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] One of the world's fastest-growing economies, Dubai's gross domestic product is projected at over US$177 billion in 2021, with a growth rate of 6.1% in 2014.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Although a number of core elements of Dubai's trading infrastructure were built on the back of the oil industry, revenues from oil and natural gas account for less than 5% of the emirate's revenues.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It is estimated that Dubai produces 50,000 to 70,000 barrels (7,900 to 11,100 m3) of oil a day and substantial quantities of gas from offshore fields.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The emirate's share in the UAE's total gas revenues is about 2%.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai's oil reserves have diminished significantly and are expected to be exhausted in 20 years.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Real estate and construction (22.6%), trade (16%), *entrepôt* (15%), and financial services (11%) are the largest contributors to Dubai's economy.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai's non-oil foreign trade stood at $362 billion in 2014.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Of the total trade volume, imports accounted for the largest share at $230 billion, while exports and re-exports to the emirate totaled $31 billion and $101 billion, respectively.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] By 2014, China had emerged as Dubai's largest international trading partner, with total trade of $47.7 billion, up 29% from 2013.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] India was second among Dubai's key trading partners, with trade totaling $29.7 billion, followed by the United States at $22.62 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia was Dubai's fourth-largest trading partner globally and its first in the GCC and the Arab world, with a total trade value of $14.2 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Trade with Germany in 2014 totalled $12.3 billion; Switzerland and Japan both at $11.72 billion; and the UK at $10.9 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Historically, Dubai and its twin across Dubai Creek, Deira (then independent of Dubai City), were important ports of call for Western manufacturers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Most of the new city's banking and financial centres were headquartered in the port area.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai remained a major trade hub throughout the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has a free trade in gold and, until the 1990s, was the hub of a "brisk smuggling trade" of gold ingots to India, where gold import was restricted.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai's Jebel Ali port, constructed in the 1970s, has the largest human-made harbour in the world and was ranked seventh globally for the volume of container traffic it supports.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is also a hub for service industries such as information technology and finance, with industry-specific free zones throughout the city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Various programmes, resources, and value-added services support the growth of startups in Dubai and help them connect to new business opportunities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Dubai Financial Market (DFM) was established in 2000 as a secondary market for trading securities and bonds, both local and foreign.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of the fourth quarter of 2006, its trading volume stood at about 400 billion shares, valued at $95 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The DFM had a market capitalisation of about $87 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The other Dubai-based stock exchange is NASDAQ Dubai, the Middle East's international stock exchange.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It enables a range of companies, including UAE and regional small and medium-sized enterprises, to trade on an exchange with an international brand name, with access to both regional and international investors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] DMCC (Dubai Multi Commodities Centre) was established in 2002.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It is the world's fastest-growing free zone and was nominated for "Global Free Zone of the Year 2016" by The *Financial Times* Magazine.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is also known as the City of Gold because a major part of the economy is based on gold trading, with Dubai's total gold trading volumes in H1 2011 reaching 580 tonnes at an average price of US$1,455 per troy ounce.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A *City Mayors* survey ranked Dubai 44th among the world's best financial cities in 2007, while another report by *City Mayors* indicated that Dubai was the world's 27th richest city in 2012, in terms of purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is also an international financial centre (IFC) and has been ranked 37th within the top 50 global financial cities as surveyed by the MasterCard Worldwide Centres of Commerce Index (2007), and first within the Middle East.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Since it opened in September 2004, the Dubai IFC has attracted leading international firms as a regional hub and has established NASDAQ Dubai, which lists equity, derivatives, structured products, Islamic bonds (sukuk), and other bonds.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Dubai IFC model is an independent risk-based regulator with a legislative system consistent with English common law.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2012, the Global City Competitiveness Index by the Economist Intelligence Unit ranked Dubai at No.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] According to its 2013 research report on the future competitiveness of cities, Dubai will rank 23rd overall in the Index in 2025.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Indians, followed by Britons and Pakistanis are the top foreign investors in Dubai real estate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has launched several major projects to support its economy and develop different sectors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] These include Dubai Fashion 2020 and Dubai Design District, which is expected to become a home to leading local and international designers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The AED 4 billion first phase of the project was completed in 2015.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of March 2024, Dubai began operating the world's biggest waste-to-energy facility, which will power approximately 135,000 homes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In July 2024, Dubai signed an agreement to develop a logistics hub for food, fruits, and vegetables, planned to be the world's largest of its kind.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] UAE Minister of Finance Sheikh Maktoum bin Mohammed was present at the signing.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2024, the city of Dubai ranked 12 out of 142 cities in the Smart City Index.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The government's decision to diversify from a trade-based, oil-reliant economy to one oriented toward services and tourism increased property value, driving property appreciation from 2004 to 2006.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A longer-term assessment of Dubai's property market, however, showed depreciation; some properties lost as much as 64% of their value from 2001 to November 2008.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The large-scale real estate development projects have led to the construction of some of the tallest skyscrapers and largest projects in the world such as the Emirates Towers, the Burj Khalifa, the Palm Islands, and the most expensive hotel, the Burj Al Arab.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai's property market experienced a major downturn in 2008 and 2009 as a result of the slowing economic climate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] By early 2009, the situation had worsened with the Great Recession taking a heavy toll on property values, construction, and employment.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] This has had a major impact on property investors in the region, some of whom were unable to release funds from investments made in property developments.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of February 2009, Dubai's foreign debt was estimated at $80 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] However, this is a tiny fraction of the world's sovereign debt.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In Dubai, many of the property owners are residents or genuine investors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] However, 2020 Data from the Centre for Advanced Defense Studies (C4ADS) revealed that several real estate owners in the city were either subject to international sanctions or involved in criminal activities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Some others were public officials, with little likelihood of purchasing it with their known incomes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The report "Dubai Uncovered" names 100 Russian oligarchs, public officials, and Europeans involved in money laundering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Benefiting from Dubai's lack of robust real estate regulations, several corrupt individuals owned properties abroad, laundered illicit funds, and invested in real estate to store their wealth.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Names of some of such questionable figures included Daniel Kinahan, Alexander Borodai, Roman Lyabikhov, Tibor Bokor, Ruslan Baisarov, Miroslav Výboh, and others.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] For years, Dubai has been labeled a major hub for illicit cash laundering, primarily through its real estate market.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Due to the UAE's lack of robust regulations and extradition treaties with many countries, fugitives have found it a perfect hideout.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The investigation was based on data leaks from 2020 and 2022, primarily from the Dubai Land Department and publicly owned utility companies.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The EU Tax Observatory and Norway's Centre for Tax Research estimated that, in 2022, foreign ownership of real estate in Dubai was approximately $160 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Until 2022, there was no obligation for real estate agents, brokers, and lawyers in Dubai to report large cash or cryptocurrency transactions to authorities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Following the February 2022 invasion of Ukraine, property prices in Dubai rose sharply as wealthy Russians began investing in the UAE's real estate market.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Since 2020, property prices in Dubai have increased by 124%.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Meanwhile, the EU Tax Observatory and Norway's Centre for Tax Research reported that Russians have invested around $6.3 billion in Dubai's existing and under-development properties since 2022.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The increase in property prices pushed out the British expatriates, and forced them to look for property outside Dubai in cities like Ras Al Khaimah.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Despite rising property prices, real estate transactions in Dubai reached an all-time high in 2024, totaling 180,987 and worth AED 522.5bn.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] This marks a 36.5% increase in transaction volume since 2023.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Tourism is an essential part of the Dubai government's strategy to maintain the flow of foreign cash.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai's lure for tourists is based mainly on shopping, but also on its ancient and modern attractions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of 2018, Dubai is the fourth-most-visited city in the world based on the number of international visitors and the fastest growing, increasing at a 10.7% rate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The city hosted 14.9 million overnight visitors in 2016 and was expected to reach 20 million tourists by 2020.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A great tourist attraction in Dubai is the Burj Khalifa, the tallest building in the world, although Jeddah Tower in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia is aiming to be taller.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has been called the "shopping capital of the Middle East".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai alone has more than 70 shopping centres, including the world's second-largest shopping centre, The Dubai Mall.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of June 2024, the Emirate real estate developer Emaar Properties announced plans to expand the 12-million-square-foot mall for 1.5 billion dirhams ($408 million), adding 240 luxury stores, along with new food outlets.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is also known for the historical souk districts on either side of its creek.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Traditionally, dhows from East Asia, China, Sri Lanka, and India discharged their cargo, and the goods would be bargained over in the souks adjacent to the docks.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Creek played a vital role in sustaining the city's community life and was the resource that originally drove Dubai's economic boom.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of September 2013, Dubai Creek has been proposed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Many boutiques and jeweler stores are in the city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is also known as "the City of Gold", as the Gold Souk in Deira houses nearly 250 gold retail shops.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Creek Park in Dubai Creek also plays a vital role in Dubai tourism as it showcases some of the most famous tourist attractions in Dubai such as the Dolphinarium, Cable Car, Camel Ride, Horse Carriage, and Exotic Birds Shows.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has a wide range of parks like Safa Park, Mushrif Park, and Hamriya Park.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Mushrif Park showcases different houses from around the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A visitor can view the architectural features of both the exterior and interior of each home.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Some of the most popular beaches in Dubai are Umm Suqeim Beach, Al Mamzar Beach Park, JBR Open Beach, Kite Beach, Black Palace Beach, and Royal Island Beach Club.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Mastercard's Global Destination Cities Index 2019 found that tourists spend more in Dubai than in any other city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2018, the country topped the list for the fourth consecutive year, with total spend of $30.82 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2019, Dubai loosened its liquor laws, allowing tourists to purchase alcohol from state-controlled stores.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Previously, alcohol was accessible only to locals with special licences.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The policy shift came as the United Arab Emirates witnessed a severe economic crisis that led to a drop in alcohol sales by volume.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2021, the UAE was ranked among the 20 most dangerous places for LGBTQ tourists to visit.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2022, several LGBTQ tourists who travelled to Dubai were deported.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In March 2022, Thai transgender model Rachaya Noppakaroon visited Dubai to perform at the Expo 2020, but was sent back because her passport gave her sex as male.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In another case, a French influencer on TikTok and Snapchat, Ibrahim Godin, was sent back from Dubai because the authorities assumed his male friend travelling with him was his boyfriend.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Ibrahim filed a complaint for "public defamation because of sexual orientation", and an investigation was opened by the Vesoul police.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] On 2 November 2011, four cities had their bids for Expo 2020 already lodged, with Dubai making a last-minute entry.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The delegation from the Bureau International des Expositions, which visited Dubai in February 2013 to examine its readiness for the largest exposition, was impressed by the infrastructure and level of national support.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In May 2013, the Dubai Expo 2020 Master Plan was revealed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai won the right to host Expo 2020 on 27 November 2013.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The leading site of Dubai Expo 2020 was planned to be a 438-hectare area (1,083 acres), part of the new *Dubai Trade Centre Jebel Ali* urban development, located midway between Dubai and Abu Dhabi.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Moreover, the Expo 2020 also created various social enlistment projects and monetary boons to the city targeting the year 2020, such as initiating the world's largest solar power project.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Due to the impact of COVID-19, the organisers of Expo 2020 postponed the Expo by one year to begin in 2021 (the new dates are 1 October 2021 to 31 March 2022).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has targets to build an inclusive, barrier-free, and disability-friendly city, which opened as Expo City Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The city has already implemented changes, including wheelchair-accessible taxis, sloped pavements, and tactile floor indicators at all metro stations for visually impaired passengers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has a rich collection of buildings and structures of various architectural styles.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As a result of this boom, modern Islamic – and world – architecture has literally been taken to new levels in skyscraper building design and technology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai now has more completed or topped-out skyscrapers higher than 2⁄3 km (2,200 ft), 1⁄3 km (1,100 ft), or 1⁄4 km (820 ft) than any other city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A culmination point was reached in 2010 with the completion of the Burj Khalifa (Khalifa Tower), now by far the world's tallest building at 829.8 m (2,722 ft).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Burj Khalifa's design is derived from the patterning systems embodied in Islamic architecture, with the triple-lobed footprint of the building based on an abstracted version of the desert flower hymenocallis which is native to the Dubai region.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The completion of the Burj Khalifa, following the construction boom that began in the 1980s, accelerated in the 1990s and reached a rapid pace during the 2000s, leaving Dubai with the world's tallest skyline as of 4 January 2010.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] At The Top in Burj Khalifa, the world's second highest observatory deck after the Shanghai Tower with an outdoor terrace, is one of Dubai's most popular tourist attractions, with over 1.87 million visitors in 2013.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Creek Tower had been planned in the 2010s to keep Dubai atop the list of tallest buildings.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] However, construction was placed on indefinite hold during the coronavirus pandemic.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] No date has been announced for the project's continuation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is recognised as a "Design City" by UNESCO's Creative Cities Network.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Burj Al Arab (Arabic: برج العرب, *Tower of the Arabs*), a luxury hotel, is frequently called "the world's only 7-star", though its management has never made that claim.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The term "7-star hotel" was coined by a British journalist to describe their experience of the hotel.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A Jumeirah Group spokesperson said: "There's not a lot we can do to stop it.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] We're not encouraging the use of the term.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] We've never used it in our advertising." The hotel opened in December 1999.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Burj Khalifa, known as the Burj Dubai before its inauguration, is a 828 metres (2,717 ft) high skyscraper in Dubai, and the tallest building in the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The structure of the desert flower inspired the tower *Hymenocallis*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It was constructed by more than 30 contracting companies worldwide, with workers from 100 nationalities, from 2004 to 2009.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It's also an architectural icon, named after Sheikh Khalifa bin Zayed Al Nahyan.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Palm Jumeirah is an artificial archipelago, created using land reclamation by Nakheel Properties, a company owned by the Dubai government, and designed and developed by Helman Hurley Charvat Peacock/Architects, Inc.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It is one of three planned islands, the Palm Islands, which extend into the Persian Gulf.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Palm Jumeirah is the smallest and the original of the three Palm Islands, and is in the Jumeirah coastal area.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The World Islands is an archipelago of small artificial islands shaped like a world map in the waters of the Persian Gulf, 4.0 kilometres (2.5 mi) off the coast of Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The World islands are mainly made of sand dredged from Dubai's shallow coastal waters and are one of several artificial island developments in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The islands' areas vary from 250,000 to 900,000 square feet.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The islands are arranged in a world map shape, and the archipelago spans about 9 km.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] On 14 February 2013, the Dubai Miracle Garden, a 72,000-metre (236,000-foot) flower garden, opened in Dubailand.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It is the world's largest flower garden.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The garden displays more than 50 million flowers with more than 70 species of flowering plants.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The garden uses treated wastewater from the city's municipality and utilises the drip irrigation method for watering the plants.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] During the summer seasons from late May to September, when the climate can get extremely hot with an average high of about 40 °C (104 °F), the garden stays closed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In January 2024, Dubai announced its intention to build the Aeternitas Tower, which will become the world's tallest residential clock tower at a height of 450 m (1,480 ft).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] That is four times the height of London's Big Ben.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The tallest clock tower to date is Makkah Clock Royal Tower in Mecca.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The tower's name, "Aeternitas", comes from the ancient Roman religion; she was the divine personification of eternity.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The project is a joint venture between Dubai-based real estate developer London Gate and Swiss luxury watch manufacturer Franck Muller.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The tower offers luxury apartments, including 1 to 4-bedroom units, as well as Sky Villas and Sky Mansions, with interiors inspired by Franck Muller's designs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Marina is an artificial canal city, built along a 3-kilometre (2 mi) stretch of Persian Gulf shoreline.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] When the entire development is complete, it will accommodate more than 120,000 people in residential towers and villas.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The 50 million square feet area of the Dubai Marina boasts a centrepiece that includes a 3.5-kilometer water canal which is the heart of the development and provides dual access to the sea, making Dubai Marina a foremost sailing destination.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It is on Interchange 5 between Jebel Ali Port and the area which hosts Dubai Internet City, Dubai Media City, and the American University in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The first phase of this project has been completed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Marina was inspired by the Concord Pacific Place development along False Creek in Vancouver, BC, Canada.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Much marine wildlife (especially whales and sharks) has entered the marina because of its proximity to the open sea.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The structure consists of two towers connected at the bottom, with a sky bridge at the top that connects the 63rd through the 77th levels.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The sky bridge houses luxury apartments on the world's highest occupiable floor at 294.36 metres.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Known as Jumeirah Gate, it opened in December 2020 and is situated along the beach.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The towers have the world's highest infinity pool in a building, on the roof, at a height of 293.906 metres.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Transport in Dubai is controlled by the Roads and Transport Authority (RTA), an agency of the government of Dubai, formed by royal decree in 2005.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The public transport network has in the past faced congestion and reliability issues which a large investment programme has addressed, including over AED 70 billion of improvements planned for completion by 2020, when the population of the city is projected to exceed 3.5 million.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2009, there were an estimated 1,021,880 cars in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In January 2010, the proportion of Dubai residents who use public transport stood at 6%.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Five main routes – E 11 (Sheikh Zayed Road), E 311 (Sheikh Mohammed Bin Zayed Road), E 44 (Dubai-Hatta Highway), E 77 (Dubai-Al Habab Road), and E 66 (Oud Metha Road, Dubai-Al Ain Road, or Tahnoun Bin Mohammad Al Nahyan Road) – run through Dubai, connecting the city to other towns and emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Additionally, several important intra-city routes, such as D 89 (Al Maktoum Road/Airport Road), D 85 (Baniyas Road), D 75 (Sheikh Rashid Road), D 73 (Al Dhiyafa Road now named as 2 December street), D 94 (Jumeirah Road), and D 92 (Al Khaleej/Al Wasl Road) connect the various localities in the city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The eastern and western sections of the city are connected by Al Maktoum Bridge, Al Garhoud Bridge, Al Shindagha Tunnel, Business Bay Crossing, and Floating Bridge.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The RTA operates Dubai's public bus transport system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The bus system services 140 routes and transports over 109 million people in 2008.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] By the end of 2010, there will be 2,100 buses in service across the city.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2006, the transport authority announced the construction of 500 air-conditioned passenger bus shelters, and planned for 1,000 more across the emirates in a move to encourage the use of public buses.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai-licensed taxis are easily identifiable by their cream bodywork, with varied roof colours indicating the operator.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Taxi Corporation, a division of the RTA, is the largest operator and operates red-roofed taxis.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] There are five private operators: Metro Taxis (orange roofs); Network Taxis (yellow roofs); Cars Taxis (blue roofs); Arabia Taxis (green roofs); and City Taxis (purple roofs).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In addition, there is a Ladies and Families taxi service (pink roofs) with female drivers, which caters exclusively to women and children.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] More than 3,000 taxis operate in the emirate, averaging 192,000 trips daily and carrying about 385,000 people.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2009, taxi trips exceeded 70 million trips, serving around 140.45 million passengers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai International Airport (IATA: DXB), the hub for the Emirates airline, serves the city of Dubai and other emirates in the country.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The airport is the third-busiest airport in the world by passenger traffic and the world's busiest airport by international passenger traffic.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In addition to being an important passenger traffic hub, the airport is the sixth-busiest cargo airport in world, handling 2.37 million tons of cargo in 2014.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Emirates is one of the national flag carriers of the United Arab Emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of 2018, it operated internationally, serving over 150 destinations in over 70 countries across six continents.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The development of Al Maktoum International Airport (IATA: DWC) was announced in 2004.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The first phase of the airport, featuring one A380-capable runway, 64 remote stands, one cargo terminal with an annual capacity for 250,000 tonnes of cargo, and a passenger terminal building designed to accommodate five million passengers per year, has been opened.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] When completed, Dubai World Central-Al Maktoum International will be the largest airport in the world with five runways, four terminal buildings, and capacity for 160 million passengers and 12 million tons of cargo.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Metro consists of two lines (Red and Green) that run through the city's financial and residential areas.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] UK-based international service company Serco is responsible for operating the metro.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Red Line is the major backbone, with 29 stations (4 underground, 24 elevated, and one at ground level) running from Rashidiya Station to UAE Xchange Station in Jebel Ali.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Green Line, running from the Etisalat Station to the Creek Station, has 20 stations (8 underground, 12 elevated).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] An extension to the Red Line connecting the EXPO 2020 site opened on 1 June 2021.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A Blue line is under construction and a Gold line is in planning.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Dubai Metro is the first urban train network in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The trains are fully automated and driverless.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A monorail line connecting the Palm Jumeirah to the mainland opened on 30 April 2009.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It is the first monorail in the Middle East.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] An extension to connect to the Red Line of the Dubai Metro is planned.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A tramway located in Al Sufouh runs for 14.5 km (9.0 mi) along Al Sufouh Road from Dubai Marina to the Burj Al Arab and the Mall of the Emirates with two interchanges with the Dubai Metro Red Line.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The first section, a 10.6 km (6.6 mi)- long tram line serving 11 stations, was opened in 2014.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Phase 2 of the tramway plans to add 4 km of track to link to the Mall of the Emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has announced it will complete a link of the UAE high-speed rail system, which is planned to link with the whole GCC (Gulf Cooperation Council, also known as Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf), and then possibly Europe.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The high-speed rail will support passengers and cargo.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Passenger trains began operation between Abu Dhabi and Fujairah on June 30, 2026, with a subsequent station in Dubai (Jumeirah Golf Estates) planned to open on 30.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] There are two major commercial ports in Dubai, Port Rashid and Port Jebel Ali.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Port Jebel Ali is the world's largest human-made harbour, the biggest port in the Middle East, and the 7th-busiest port in the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] One of the more traditional methods of getting across Bur Dubai to Deira is by *abras*, small boats that ferry passengers across the Dubai Creek, between abra stations in Bastakiya and Baniyas Road.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Marine Transport Agency has also implemented the Dubai Water Bus System.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The water bus is a fully air-conditioned boat service connecting selected destinations across the creek.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] One can also use the tourist water bus service in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The latest addition to the water transport system is the Water Taxi.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Water-Taxis can transport a maximum of 20 passengers at a time which provides a smooth journey along Al Mamzar and Dubai Marina via Dubai Creek.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is increasingly leveraging its logistics and ports to participate in trade between Europe and China, as well as between Europe and Africa, in addition to oil transport.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] For this purpose, ports such as Jebel Ali and Mina Rashid are rapidly expanded, and investments are made in their technology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The UAE's culture mainly reflects traditional Arab culture.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The influence of Arab and Islamic cultures on architecture, music, attire, cuisine, and lifestyle is also pronounced.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Five times a day, Muslims are called to prayer from the minarets of mosques scattered across the country.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Major holidays in Dubai include Eid al-Fitr, which marks the end of Ramadan, and National Day (2 December), which marks the formation of the United Arab Emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The city's cultural imprint as a small, ethnically homogeneous pearling community was transformed by the arrival of other ethnic groups and nationals—first by Iranians in the early 1900s, and later by Indians and Pakistanis in the 1960s.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2005, 84% of Dubai's metropolitan population was foreign-born, about half of whom were from India.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] From 2006 to 2022, the weekend had been Friday and Saturday, as a compromise between Friday's holiness to Muslims and the Western weekend of Saturday and Sunday.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Before 2006, the weekend was Thursday-Friday.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] On 1 January 2022, Dubai moved to a four-and-a-half-day working week, with the weekend comprising Friday afternoon, Saturday, and Sunday with stringent rules for foreign migrant workers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Because of the tourism-driven entrepreneurial approach of many Dubai residents and the high standard of living, Dubai's culture has gradually evolved toward luxury, opulence, and lavishness, with a strong emphasis on leisure-related extravagance.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Clubs and bars are chiefly found in hotels due to liquor laws.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] *The New York Times* called Dubai "the kind of city where you might run into Michael Jordan at the Buddha Bar or stumble across Naomi Campbell celebrating her birthday with a multiday bash".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Annual entertainment events such as the Dubai Shopping Festival (DSF) and Dubai Summer Surprises (DSS) attract over 4 million visitors from across the region and generate revenues over $2.7 billion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The International Festivals and Events Association (IFEA), the world's leading events trade association, has crowned Dubai as *IFEA World Festival and Event City, 2012* in the cities category with a population of more than one million.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Arabic cuisine is popular and is available everywhere in the city, from the small *shawarma* diners in Deira and Al Karama to the restaurants in Dubai's hotels.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Fast food, South Asian, and Chinese cuisines are also very popular and are widely available.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The sale and consumption of pork is regulated and is legally permitted to be sold only to non-Muslims, in designated areas of supermarkets and airports.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Similarly, the sale of alcoholic beverages is also regulated.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A liquor permit is required to purchase alcohol, but it is available at hotel bars and restaurants.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] *Shisha* and *qahwa* boutiques are also popular in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The inaugural Dubai Food Festival was held between 21 February and 15 March 2014.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The event was aimed at celebrating Dubai's position as the gastronomic capital region.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The festival was designed to showcase the variety of flavours and cuisines on offer in Dubai, featuring dishes from over 200 nationalities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The next food festival was held between 23 February 2017 and 11 March 2017.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Opera opened its doors on 31 August 2016 in Downtown Dubai with a performance by Plácido Domingo.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The venue is a 2000-seat, multifunctional performing arts centre that can host not only theatrical shows, concerts, and operas, but also weddings, gala dinners, banquets, and conferences.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Arabic movies are popular in Dubai and the UAE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Since 2004, the city has hosted the annual Dubai International Film Festival which serves as a showcase for Arab and Middle Eastern filmmaking talent.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Dubai Desert Rock Festival was also another major festival consisting of heavy metal and rock artists but is no longer held in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] One of the lesser-known sides of Dubai is the importance of its young contemporary art gallery scene.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Since 2008, the leading contemporary art galleries such as Carbon 12 Dubai, Green Art, gallery Isabelle van den Eynde, and The Third Line have brought the city onto the international art map.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Art Dubai, the region's growing and reputable art fair, is also a major contributor to the development of the contemporary art scene.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Theatre of Digital Art Dubai (ToDA) opened in 2020 and presents immersive digital art, including contemporary work.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Many international news agencies, such as Reuters, APTN, Bloomberg L.P., and Middle East Broadcasting Centre (MBC), operate in Dubai Media City and Dubai Internet City.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Additionally, several local network television channels, such as Dubai One (formerly Channel 33) and Dubai TV (EDTV), provide programming in English and Arabic, respectively.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai is also the headquarters for several print media outlets.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] *Dar Al Khaleej*, *Al Bayan*, and *Al Ittihad* are the city's largest circulating Arabic language newspapers, while *Gulf News*, *Khaleej Times*, *Khaleej Mag*, and *7days* are the largest circulating English newspapers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Etisalat, the government-owned telecommunications provider, held a virtual monopoly over telecommunications services in Dubai before the establishment of other, smaller telecommunications companies, such as Emirates Integrated Telecommunications Company (EITC—better known as Du) in 2006.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Internet was introduced into the UAE (and therefore Dubai) in 1995.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The network has an Internet bandwidth of 7.5 Gbit/s and supports 49 STM-1 links.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai houses two of four Domain Name System (DNS) data centres in the country (DXBNIC1, DXBNIC2).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Censorship is common in Dubai and used by the government to control content that it believes violates the cultural and political sensitivities of Emirates.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Homosexuality, drugs, and the theory of evolution are generally considered taboo.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Etisalat uses a proxy server to filter Internet content the government deems inconsistent with the values of the country, such as sites that provide information on how to bypass the proxy; sites about dating, gay and lesbian networks, and pornography; and formerly sites originating from Israel.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Emirates Media and Internet (a division of Etisalat) notes that as of 2002, 76% of Internet users are male.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] About 60% of Internet users were Asian, and 25% were Arab.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai enacted the Electronic Transactions and Commerce Law in 2002, which addresses digital signatures and electronic registers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It prohibits Internet Service Providers (ISPs) from disclosing information gathered in the course of providing services.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The penal code contains official provisions that prohibit digital access to pornography; however, it does not address cyber crime or data protection.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2019, the Italian artist Princess Bee produced "Hi Dubai", the first cross-media project that reveals the "soul of the city" through the life and work experiences of 25 Emirati and expat women.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The series also promoted the Emirati lifestyle and events to attract young people to visit and live in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] "Hi Dubai" aired during prime time (after the National News and during the UAE National Day week) on Dubai One.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It was then distributed online through Dubai Post and shown in ICE, the in-flight entertainment system of the Emirates airline.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Football and cricket are the most popular sports in Dubai.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The International Cricket Council is headquartered there.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Three football teams (Al Wasl FC, Shabab Al-Ahli Dubai FC, and Al Nasr SC) represent Dubai in UAE Pro-League.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Al-Wasl have the second-most championships in the UAE League, after Al Ain.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai also hosts both the annual Dubai Tennis Championships and The Legends Rock Dubai tennis tournaments, as well as the Dubai Desert Classic golf tournament and the DP World Tour Championship, all of which attract sports stars from around the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Dubai World Cup, a thoroughbred horse race, is held annually at the Meydan Racecourse.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The city's top basketball team has traditionally been Shabab Al Ahli Basket.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai also hosts the traditional rugby union tournament, Dubai Sevens, part of the Sevens World Series.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2009, Dubai hosted the 2009 Rugby World Cup Sevens.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Auto racing is also a major sport in Dubai; the Dubai Autodrome hosts many auto racing events throughout the year.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Another sporting event in Dubai is the Dubai Run, which is part of the Dubai Fitness Challenge and the world's largest free fun run, a main highlight of the challenge since 2017.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It also features a state-of-the-art indoor and outdoor Kartdrome, popular among racing enthusiasts and recreational riders.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Indian Premier League cricket competition was held in the UAE in 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] On 12 June, Tommy Fleetwood, 7-time DP World Tour winner, was declared World Global Ambassador.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2025, Dubai introduced the "Dubai Sports Strategy 2033", a long-term framework designed to support the emirate's sports sector and strengthen its position as a global sports destination.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The strategy outlines initiatives to expand community participation in physical activity, enhance the quality and number of sporting events, and develop local talent across multiple disciplines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] It also aims to increase the economic contribution of Dubai's sports industry through targeted programmes and infrastructure development.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The Emirati attire is typical of several countries in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Women usually wear the "abaya", a long black robe, with a hijab (a headscarf that covers the neck and part of the head, all of the hair and the ears).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Some women may wear a niqab that covers the mouth and nose, leaving only the eyes exposed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Men wear the "kandurah" also referred to as "dishdasha" or even "thawb" (long white robe) and the headscarf (ghotrah).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The traditional ghutrah in the UAE is white and held in place by an accessory called "egal", which resembles a black cord.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Younger Emiratis prefer to wear red-and-white ghutrah and tie them around their heads like turbans.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The dress code is never compulsory; many people wear Western or other Eastern clothing.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] However, prohibitions on "indecent clothing" or revealing too much skin are aspects of the UAE to which Dubai's visitors are expected to conform and are encoded in Dubai's criminal law.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The UAE has enforced decency regulations in most public places, aside from waterparks, beaches, clubs, and bars.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The school system in Dubai follows the United Arab Emirates' system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] As of 2009, there are 79 public schools run by the Ministry of Education that serve Emiratis and expatriate Arab people, as well as 207 private schools.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The medium of instruction in public schools is Arabic with emphasis on English as a second language, while most of the private schools use English as their medium of instruction.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Currently, only the Swiss International Scientific School in Dubai claims to offer parallel streams in different languages – bilingual English/French or English/German.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Most private schools cater to one or more expatriate communities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Some 36 schools offer international education using one or more of the four International Baccalaureate Programmes for students aged 3–19.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Currently, 15 schools have introduced the IB Career-related Programme that can be combined with a vocational qualification such as a BTEC.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] While there are more UK-curriculum-based schools in Dubai than any other curriculum, more students attend Indian-curriculum schools, which tend to be considerably larger and cost less to attend.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] There are 34 Indian-curriculum schools in the emirate, most of which offer the CBSE, and just a handful the Indian Certificate of Secondary Education (ICSE) Indian syllabus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Examples of Indian-curriculum schools include IHS, DPS, and DMHS.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] There are a small number of Pakistani schools in Dubai offering the FBISE curriculum for expatriate children.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A total of 18 schools offer British primary education through age 11.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] There are 64 schools that offer a variation of a UK curriculum style secondary education, either a pure GCSE and A-Level offering, or increasingly I/GCSE up to 16, and then the IB Diploma post-16.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Currently, no school in the UAE offers IB or A-level courses at age 16, but several schools have said they will offer them in the future.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] British style eleven-to-eighteen secondary schools offering General Certificate of Secondary Education and A-Levels include Dubai College, Dubai British School, and English Language School Pvt.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Some schools, such as The American School of Dubai, also offer the curriculum of the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai has a very active education regulator, the KHDA, which is best known for its school ratings, but actually has a wide mandate when it comes to school improvement in the emirate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] A total of 17 schools are currently rated Outstanding (2020), and a further 40 are rated Very Good.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] They offer courses in all major subjects, with the most popular subject areas being Business, followed by Information Technology, then Engineering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Most Universities in Dubai are located in the two Educational Zones (Knowledge Village or Academic City).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2013, Synergy University Dubai Campus opened its campus in Jumeirah Lakes Towers being a first University in Dubai to be located outside of Educational Zones (Knowledge Village or Academic City).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Only 4 Dubai Universities are present in the QS World University Rankings 2024/2025.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] To allow the assessment of more UAE Universities, the Ministry of Education launched The National Higher Education Institutions Classification Framework which classifies UAE Universities based on their research and teaching.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Of the top 10 largest Dubai universities University of Wollongong in Dubai, American University in Dubai, and Rochester Institute of Technology of Dubai, were all classified as "Very Good" within The National Higher Education Institutions Classification Framework.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Healthcare in Dubai can be divided into two different sectors: public and private.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Each Emirate can set healthcare standards in accordance with its internal laws, though the standards and regulations rarely differ significantly.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Public hospitals in Dubai were first established in the late 1950s and continued to expand alongside public health initiatives.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] There are now 28 hospitals in Dubai, six public and 22 private, with three more major hospitals scheduled to be built by 2025.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] By the end of 2012, there were also a total of 1,348 medical clinics, 97% of which were operated privately.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] In 2015, Dubai phased in mandatory health insurance for all inhabitants, thereby leading to increased demand for medical services.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Dubai Hospital is a public hospital in Dubai and is part of Dubai Department of Health and Medical Services.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] Although the decision to construct Dubai Hospital was made in 1977, it did not begin admitting patients until March 1983.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/dubai-p02] The hospital consists of 14 stories, with the lower two for Accident & Emergency and outpatients, and the upper ten floors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanotechnology defined by scale includes fields of science such as surface science, organic chemistry, molecular biology, semiconductor physics, energy storage, engineering, microfabrication, and molecular engineering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The associated research and applications range from extensions of conventional device physics to molecular self-assembly, from developing new materials with dimensions on the nanoscale to direct control of matter on the atomic scale.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanotechnology may be able to create new materials and devices with diverse applications, such as in nanomedicine, nanoelectronics, agricultural sectors, biomaterials energy production, and consumer products.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] However, nanotechnology raises issues, including concerns about the toxicity and environmental impact of nanomaterials, and their potential effects on global economics, as well as various doomsday scenarios.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These concerns have led to a debate among advocacy groups and governments on whether special regulation of nanotechnology is warranted.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The concepts that seeded nanotechnology were first discussed in 1959 by physicist Richard Feynman in his talk *There's Plenty of Room at the Bottom*, in which he described the possibility of synthesis via direct manipulation of atoms.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The term "nano-technology" was first used by Norio Taniguchi in 1974, though it was not widely known.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Eric Drexler used the term "nanotechnology" in his 1986 book *Engines of Creation: The Coming Era of Nanotechnology*, which achieved popular success and helped thrust nanotechnology into the public sphere.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In it, he proposed the idea of a nanoscale "assembler" that would be able to build a copy of itself and of other items of arbitrary complexity with atom-level control.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Also in 1986, Drexler co-founded The Foresight Institute to increase public awareness and understanding of nanotechnology concepts and implications.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The emergence of nanotechnology as a field in the 1980s occurred through the convergence of Drexler's theoretical and public work, which developed and popularized a conceptual framework, and experimental advances that drew additional attention to the prospects.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In the 1980s, two breakthroughs helped to spark the growth of nanotechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] First, the invention of the scanning tunneling microscope in 1981 enabled visualization of individual atoms and bonds, and was successfully used to manipulate individual atoms in 1989.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The microscope's developers Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer at IBM Zurich Research Laboratory received a Nobel Prize in Physics in 1986.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Binnig, Quate and Gerber also invented the analogous atomic force microscope that year.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Second, fullerenes (buckyballs) were discovered in 1985 by Harry Kroto, Richard Smalley, and Robert Curl, who together won the 1996 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] C60 was not initially described as nanotechnology; the term was used regarding subsequent work with related carbon nanotubes (sometimes called graphene tubes or Bucky tubes) which suggested potential applications for nanoscale electronics and devices.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The discovery of carbon nanotubes is attributed to Sumio Iijima of NEC in 1991, for which Iijima won the inaugural 2008 Kavli Prize in Nanoscience.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In the early 2000s, the field garnered increased scientific, political, and commercial attention that led to both controversy and progress.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Controversies emerged regarding the definitions and potential implications of nanotechnologies, exemplified by the Royal Society's report on nanotechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Challenges were raised regarding the feasibility of applications envisioned by advocates of molecular nanotechnology, which culminated in a public debate between Drexler and Smalley in 2001 and 2003.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Meanwhile, commercial products based on advancements in nanoscale technologies began emerging.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These products were limited to bulk applications of nanomaterials and did not involve atomic control of matter.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Some examples include the Silver Nano platform for using silver nanoparticles as an antibacterial agent, nanoparticle-based sunscreens, carbon fiber strengthening using silica nanoparticles, and carbon nanotubes for stain-resistant textiles.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] By the mid-2000s scientific attention began to flourish.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanotechnology roadmaps centered on atomically precise manipulation of matter and discussed existing and projected capabilities, goals, and applications.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanotechnology is the science and engineering of functional systems at the molecular scale.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In its original sense, nanotechnology refers to the projected ability to construct items from the bottom up making complete, high-performance products.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] One nanometer (nm) is one billionth, or 10−9, of a meter.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] By comparison, typical carbon–carbon bond lengths, or the spacing between these atoms in a molecule, are in the range 0.12–0.15 nm, and DNA's diameter is around 2 nm.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] On the other hand, the smallest cellular life forms, the bacteria of the genus *Mycoplasma*, are around 200 nm in length.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] By convention, nanotechnology is taken as the scale range 1 to 100 nm, following the definition used by the American National Nanotechnology Initiative.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The lower limit is set by the size of atoms (hydrogen has the smallest atoms, which have an approximately ,25 nm kinetic diameter).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The upper limit is more or less arbitrary, but is around the size below which phenomena not observed in larger structures start to become apparent and can be made use of.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These phenomena make nanotechnology distinct from devices that are merely miniaturized versions of an equivalent macroscopic device; such devices are on a larger scale and come under the description of microtechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] To put that scale in another context, the comparative size of a nanometer to a meter is the same as that of a marble to the size of the earth.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Two main approaches are used in nanotechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In the "bottom-up" approach, materials and devices are built from molecular components which assemble themselves chemically by principles of molecular recognition.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In the "top-down" approach, nano-objects are constructed from larger entities without atomic-level control.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Areas of physics such as nanoelectronics, nanomechanics, nanophotonics and nanoionics have evolved to provide nanotechnology's scientific foundation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Several phenomena become pronounced as system size.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These include statistical mechanical effects, as well as quantum mechanical effects, for example, the "quantum size effect" in which the electronic properties of solids alter along with reductions in particle size.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Such effects do not apply at macro or micro dimensions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] However, quantum effects can become significant when nanometer scales.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Additionally, physical (mechanical, electrical, optical, etc.) properties change versus macroscopic systems.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] One example is the increase in surface area to volume ratio altering mechanical, thermal, and catalytic properties of materials.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Diffusion and reactions can be different as well.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Systems with fast ion transport are referred to as nanoionics.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The mechanical properties of nanosystems are of interest in research.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Modern synthetic chemistry can prepare small molecules of almost any structure.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These methods are used to manufacture a wide variety of useful chemicals such as pharmaceuticals or commercial polymers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] This ability raises the question of extending this kind of control to the next-larger level, seeking methods to assemble single molecules into supramolecular assemblies consisting of many molecules arranged in a well-defined manner.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These approaches utilize the concepts of molecular self-assembly and/or supramolecular chemistry to automatically arrange themselves into a useful conformation through a bottom-up approach.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The concept of molecular recognition is important: molecules can be designed so that a specific configuration or arrangement is favored due to non-covalent intermolecular forces.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The Watson–Crick basepairing rules are a direct result of this, as is the specificity of an enzyme targeting a single substrate, or the specific folding of a protein.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Thus, components can be designed to be complementary and mutually attractive so that they make a more complex and useful whole.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Such bottom-up approaches should be capable of producing devices in parallel and be much cheaper than top-down methods, but could potentially be overwhelmed as the size and complexity of the desired assembly increases.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Most useful structures require complex and thermodynamically unlikely arrangements of atoms.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nevertheless, many examples of self-assembly based on molecular recognition in exist in biology, most notably Watson–Crick basepairing and enzyme-substrate interactions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Molecular nanotechnology, sometimes called molecular manufacturing, concerns engineered nanosystems (nanoscale machines) operating on the molecular scale.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Molecular nanotechnology is especially associated with molecular assemblers, machines that can produce a desired structure or device atom-by-atom using the principles of mechanosynthesis.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Manufacturing in the context of productive nanosystems is not related to conventional technologies used to manufacture nanomaterials such as carbon nanotubes and nanoparticles.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] When Drexler independently coined and popularized the term "nanotechnology", he envisioned manufacturing technology based on molecular machine systems.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The premise was that molecular-scale biological analogies of traditional machine components demonstrated molecular machines were possible: biology was full of examples of sophisticated, stochastically optimized biological machines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The physics and engineering performance of exemplar designs were analyzed in Drexler's book *Nanosystems: Molecular Machinery, Manufacturing, and Computation*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In general, assembling devices on the atomic scale requires positioning atoms on other atoms of comparable size and stickiness.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Carlo Montemagno's view is that future nanosystems will be hybrids of silicon technology and biological molecular machines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Richard Smalley argued that mechanosynthesis was impossible due to difficulties in mechanically manipulating individual molecules.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] This led to an exchange of letters in the American Chemical Society publication *Chemical & Engineering News* in 2003.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Though biology clearly demonstrates that molecular machines are possible, non-biological molecular machines remained in their infancy.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Alex Zettl and colleagues at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratories and UC Berkeley constructed at least three molecular devices whose motion is controlled via changing voltage: a nanotube nanomotor, a molecular actuator, and a nanoelectromechanical relaxation oscillator.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Ho and Lee at Cornell University in 1999 used a scanning tunneling microscope to move an individual carbon monoxide molecule (CO) to an individual iron atom (Fe) sitting on a flat silver crystal and chemically bound the CO to the Fe by applying a voltage.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Many areas of science develop or study materials having unique properties arising from their nanoscale dimensions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The bottom-up approach seeks to arrange smaller components into more complex assemblies.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These seek to create smaller devices by using larger ones to direct their assembly.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Functional approaches seek to develop useful components without regard to how they might be assembled.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These subfields seek to anticipate what inventions nanotechnology might yield, or attempt to propose an agenda along which inquiry could progress.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These often take a big-picture view, with more emphasis on societal implications than engineering details.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanomaterials can be classified in 0D, 1D, 2D and 3D nanomaterials.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Dimensionality plays a major role in determining the characteristic of nanomaterials including physical, chemical, and biological characteristics.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] With the decrease in dimensionality, an increase in surface-to-volume ratio is observed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] This indicates that smaller dimensional nanomaterials have higher surface area compared to 3D nanomaterials.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Two dimensional (2D) nanomaterials have been extensively investigated for electronic, biomedical, drug delivery and biosensor applications.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The atomic force microscope (AFM) and the scanning tunneling microscope (STM) are two versions of scanning probes that are used for nano-scale observation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Other types of scanning probe microscopy have much higher resolution, since they are not limited by the wavelengths of sound or light.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The tip of a scanning probe can also be used to manipulate nanostructures (positional assembly).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Feature-oriented scanning may be a promising way to implement these nano-scale manipulations via an automatic algorithm.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] However, this is still a slow process because of low velocity of the microscope.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] The top-down approach anticipates nanodevices that must be built piece by piece in stages, much as manufactured items are made.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Scanning probe microscopy is an important technique both for characterization and synthesis.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Atomic force microscopes and scanning tunneling microscopes can be used to look at surfaces and to move atoms around.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] By designing different tips for these microscopes, they can be used for carving out structures on surfaces and to help guide self-assembling structures.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] By using, for example, feature-oriented scanning approach, atoms or molecules can be moved around on a surface with scanning probe microscopy techniques.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Various techniques of lithography, such as optical lithography, X-ray lithography, dip pen lithography, electron beam lithography or nanoimprint lithography offer top-down fabrication techniques where a bulk material is reduced to a nano-scale pattern.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In contrast, bottom-up techniques build or grow larger structures atom by atom or molecule by molecule.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These techniques include chemical synthesis, self-assembly and positional assembly.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Dual-polarization interferometry is one tool suitable for characterization of self-assembled thin films.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Another variation of the bottom-up approach is molecular-beam epitaxy or MBE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Researchers at Bell Telephone Laboratories including John R.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Gossard developed and implemented MBE as a research tool in the late 1960s and 1970s.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Samples made by MBE were key to the discovery of the fractional quantum Hall effect for which the 1998 Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] MBE lays down atomically precise layers of atoms and, in the process, build up complex structures.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Important for research on semiconductors, MBE is also widely used to make samples and devices for the newly emerging field of spintronics.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Therapeutic products based on responsive nanomaterials, such as the highly deformable, stress-sensitive transfersome vesicles, are approved for human use in some countries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] As of August 21, 2008, the Project on Emerging Nanotechnologies estimated that over 800 manufacturer-identified nanotech products were publicly available, with new ones hitting the market at a pace of 3–4 per week.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In the electric car industry, single wall carbon nanotubes (SWCNTs) address key lithium-ion battery challenges, including energy density, charge rate, service life, and cost.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] SWCNTs connect electrode particles during charge/discharge process, preventing battery premature degradation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Their exceptional ability to wrap active material particles enhanced electrical conductivity and physical properties, setting them apart multi-walled carbon nanotubes and carbon black.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Further applications allow tennis balls to last longer, golf balls to fly straighter, and bowling balls to become more durable.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Trousers and socks have been infused with nanotechnology to last longer and lower temperature in the summer.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Bandages are infused with silver nanoparticles to heal cuts faster.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Video game consoles and personal computers may become cheaper, faster, and contain more memory thanks to nanotechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Also, to build structures for on chip computing with light, for example on chip optical quantum information processing, and picosecond transmission of information.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanotechnology may have the ability to make existing medical applications cheaper and easier to use in places like the doctors' offices and at homes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Cars use nanomaterials in such ways that car parts require fewer metals during manufacturing and less fuel to operate in the future.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanoencapsulation involves the enclosure of active substances within carriers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Typically, these carriers offer advantages, such as enhanced bioavailability, controlled release, targeted delivery, and protection of the encapsulated substances.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] In the medical field, nanoencapsulation plays a significant role in drug delivery.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] It facilitates more efficient drug administration, reduces side effects, and increases treatment effectiveness.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanoencapsulation is particularly useful for improving the bioavailability of poorly water-soluble drugs, enabling controlled and sustained drug release, and supporting the development of targeted therapies.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These features collectively contribute to advancements in medical treatments and patient care.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanotechnology may play role in tissue engineering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] When designing scaffolds, researchers attempt to mimic the nanoscale features of a cell's microenvironment to direct its differentiation down a suitable lineage.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] For example, when creating scaffolds to support bone growth, researchers may mimic osteoclast resorption pits.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Researchers used DNA origami-based nanobots capable of carrying out logic functions to target drug delivery in cockroaches.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] A nano bible (a .5mm2 silicon chip) was created by the Technion in order to increase youth interest in nanotechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] One concern is the effect that industrial-scale manufacturing and use of nanomaterials will have on human health and the environment, as suggested by nanotoxicology research.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] For these reasons, some groups advocate that nanotechnology be regulated.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] However, regulation might stifle scientific research and the development of beneficial innovations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Public health research agencies, such as the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health research potential health effects stemming from exposures to nanoparticles.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Nanoparticle products may have unintended consequences.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Researchers have discovered that bacteriostatic silver nanoparticles used in socks to reduce foot odor are released in the wash.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] These particles are then flushed into the wastewater stream and may destroy bacteria that are critical components of natural ecosystems, farms, and waste treatment processes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Experts, including director of the Woodrow Wilson Center's Project on Emerging Nanotechnologies David Rejeski, testified that commercialization depends on adequate oversight, risk research strategy, and public engagement.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] As of 206 Berkeley, California was the only US city to regulate nanotechnology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Inhaling airborne nanoparticles and nanofibers may contribute to pulmonary diseases, e.g. fibrosis.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Researchers found that when rats breathed in nanoparticles, the particles settled in the brain and lungs, which led to significant increases in biomarkers for inflammation and stress response and that nanoparticles induce skin aging through oxidative stress in hairless mice.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] A two-year study at UCLA's School of Public Health found lab mice consuming nano-titanium dioxide showed DNA and chromosome damage to a degree "linked to all the big killers of man, namely cancer, heart disease, neurological disease and aging".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] A *Nature Nanotechnology* study suggested that some forms of carbon nanotubes could be as harmful as asbestos if inhaled in sufficient quantities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Anthony Seaton of the Institute of Occupational Medicine in Edinburgh, Scotland, who contributed to the article on carbon nanotubes said "We know that some of them probably have the potential to cause mesothelioma.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] So those sorts of materials need to be handled very carefully." In the absence of specific regulation forthcoming from governments, Paull and Lyons (2008) have called for an exclusion of engineered nanoparticles in food.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] A newspaper article reports that workers in a paint factory developed serious lung disease and nanoparticles were found in their lungs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Calls for tighter regulation of nanotechnology have accompanied a debate related to human health and safety risks.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Some regulatory agencies cover some nanotechnology products and processes – by "bolting on" nanotechnology to existing regulations – leaving clear gaps.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Davies proposed a road map describing steps to deal with these shortcomings.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Andrew Maynard, chief science advisor to the Woodrow Wilson Center's Project on Emerging Nanotechnologies, reported insufficient funding for human health and safety research, and as a result inadequate understanding of human health and safety risks.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/nanotechnology] Some academics called for stricter application of the precautionary principle, slowing marketing approval, enhanced labelling and additional safety data.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University is a member of the Association of American Universities and is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue enrolls the largest student body of any individual university campus in Indiana, as well as the ninth-largest foreign student population of any university in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university is home to the world's oldest computer science degree-granting department and the first university-owned airport in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue is the founding member of the Big Ten Conference and sponsors 18 intercollegiate sports teams.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 1865, the Indiana General Assembly voted to take advantage of the Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act of 1862 and began plans to establish an institution with a focus on agriculture and engineering with the preliminary name of the Indiana Agricultural College.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Communities throughout the state offered facilities and funding in bids for the location of the new college.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Popular proposals included designating Indiana University or what is now Butler University as Indiana's land-grant, as well as the addition of an agriculture department at what is now Indiana State University.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] By 1869, Tippecanoe County's offer included $150,000 (equivalent to $3.6 million in 2025) from Lafayette business leader and philanthropist John Purdue; $50,000 from the county; and 100 acres (0.4 km2) of land from John Purdue and local residents.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] On May 6, 1869, the General Assembly established the institution in Tippecanoe County as Purdue University, in the name of the principal benefactor.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Classes began at Purdue on September 16, 1874, with six instructors and 39 students.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Hougham was Purdue's first faculty member and served as acting president between the administrations of presidents Shortridge and White.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] A campus of five buildings was completed by the end of 1874.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Allen Oren Haynes, the State Librarian of Indiana, was appointed professor of botany.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue issued its first degree, a Bachelor of Science in chemistry, in 1875.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The first female student was admitted that autumn.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] White, the university's president from 1876 to 1883, followed a strict interpretation of the Morrill Act.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Rather than emulate the classical universities, White believed Purdue should be an "industrial college" and devote its resources toward providing a broad, liberal education with an emphasis on science, technology, and agriculture.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Part of White's plan to distinguish Purdue from classical universities included a controversial attempt to ban fraternities, which was ultimately overturned by the Indiana Supreme Court.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Smart, is remembered for his call in 1894 to rebuild the original Heavilon Hall "one brick higher" after it had been destroyed by a fire.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] By the end of the nineteenth century, the university was organized into schools of agriculture, engineering (mechanical, civil, and electrical), and pharmacy; former U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] President Benjamin Harrison served on the board of trustees.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's engineering laboratories included testing facilities for a locomotive, and for a Corliss steam engine—one of the most efficient engines of the time.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Programs in education and home economics were soon established, as well as a short-lived school of medicine.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] By 1925, Purdue had the largest undergraduate engineering enrollment in the country, a status it would keep for half a century.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Elliott oversaw a campus building program between the world wars.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Ross coordinated several fundraisers, donated lands to the university, and was instrumental in establishing the Purdue Research Foundation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Ross's gifts and fundraisers supported such projects as Ross–Ade Stadium, the Memorial Union, a civil engineering surveying camp, and Purdue University Airport.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue Airport was the country's first university-owned airport and the site of the country's first college-credit flight training courses.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Amelia Earhart joined the Purdue faculty in 1935 as a consultant for these flight courses and as a counselor on women's careers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 1936, the Purdue Research Foundation provided the funds for the Lockheed Electra 10-E Earhart flew on her attempted round-the-world flight.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Every school and department at the university was involved in some type of military research or training during World War II.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] During a project on radar receivers, Purdue physicists discovered properties of germanium that led to the making of the first transistor.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Army and the Navy conducted training programs at Purdue and more than 17,500 students, staff, and alumni served in the armed forces.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue set up about a hundred centers throughout Indiana to train skilled workers for defense industries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] As veterans returned to the university under the G.I.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Bill, first-year classes were taught at some of these sites to alleviate the demand for campus space.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Four of these sites are now degree-granting regional campuses of the Purdue University system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] On-campus housing became racially desegregated in 1947.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] After the war, a decade-long construction program emphasized science and research.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In the late 1950s and early 1960s the university established programs in veterinary medicine, industrial management, and nursing, as well as the first computer science department in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Undergraduate humanities courses were strengthened, graduate-level study in these areas were slowly established.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue awarded its first Bachelor of Arts degrees in 1960.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The official seal of Purdue was officially inaugurated during the university's centennial in 1969.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Consisting of elements from emblems that had been used unofficially since the 1890s, the current seal depicts a griffin, symbolizing strength, and a three-part shield, representing education, research, and service.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 1975, Purdue University joined ARPANET, an early packet-switching network that would ultimately become the foundation for the modern internet.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In recent years, Purdue's leaders have continued to support high-tech research and international programs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] President Ronald Reagan visited the West Lafayette campus to give a speech about the influence of technological progress on job creation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In the 1990s, the university added more opportunities to study abroad and expanded its course offerings in world languages and cultures.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The first buildings of the Discovery Park interdisciplinary research center were dedicated in 2004.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] On April 27, 2017, Purdue University announced plans to acquire for-profit college Kaplan University and convert it to a public university in the state of Indiana, subject to multiple levels of approval.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] That school now operates as Purdue University Global, and aims to serve adult learners.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] On July 1, 2024, Purdue launched Purdue University in Indianapolis, an extension of the West Lafayette campus, after the formal split of Indiana University–Purdue University Indianapolis.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It conveys Purdue West Lafayette degrees and has the same academic rigor as the flagship campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue currently has a 28-acre (11 ha) footprint in downtown Indianapolis that includes space in the existing engineering and technology buildings, and has established partnerships with companies for facilities and shared spaces throughout the metro area.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue had black graduates by the 1890s, and in 1905 a Black man ran for its track team.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] But some time in the 1910s the teams became segregated, and remained so until a student protest in 1947.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Black students were not allowed to live in the residence halls until the 1940s.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Black males were able to live in cooperatives, but Black females were not allowed to live anywhere in West Lafayette.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 1946, the women's dormitories were integrated by an order of the governor of Indiana.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Helen Williams became the first Black faculty member in 1968.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university also terminated the Recruitment and Diversity Office for the Polytechnic Institute, despite diversity only being a small part of the office's function.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Terminated staff members believed that it was because of the name alone that the office was terminated, as other recruitment offices for different parts of the university that did not have "diversity" in the name had remained untouched.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In June of that year, the Indiana General Assembly passed a state budget bill mandating that Indiana's public universities phase out programs that produce fewer than a certain number of graduates over a three-year period.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] As a result, Purdue eliminated or merged a number of master's and Ph.D. programs in areas such as microbiology, mathematics, and literature.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's campus is situated in the city of West Lafayette, near the western bank of the Wabash River, across which sits the larger city of Lafayette.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Mitch Daniels Boulevard (formerly State Street) divides the northern and southern portions of campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Academic buildings are mostly concentrated on the eastern and southern parts of campus, with residence halls and intramural fields to the west, and athletic facilities to the north.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] An extensive system of underground tunnels protects pedestrians from snow, ice, wind, rain and UV during movements between buildings.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Mall is the central quad of Purdue University and was created to connect the academic campus with Ross-Ade Stadium.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It is also known as the Engineering Mall due to its proximity to several engineering buildings.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The most prominent feature of the Purdue Mall is the 38-foot (12 m)-tall concrete Engineering Fountain.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Bell Tower is between the Stadium and Centennial Malls.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Bell Tower is considered an icon of the university and can be found on many Purdue logos and those of the cities of Lafayette and West Lafayette.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Southwest of the Stadium Mall is the Edward C.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Elliott Hall of Music, one of the largest proscenium theaters in the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Elliott Hall of Music serves as the home of the WBAA (AM) and WBAA-FM studios, and was the base of operations for Purdue Bands and Orchestras until the completion of the Marc and Sharon Hagle Hall in 2022.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] West of the Elliott Hall of Music is the Armory Building.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Armory Building was rebuilt in 1918 after a fire and houses the university's ROTC programs and other clubs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Memorial Mall, south of the Purdue Mall, is the original section of campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It is a popular meeting place for students and is surrounded by other buildings used for academic and cultural purposes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Near this section of campus is Felix Haas Hall, which was constructed in 1909 as Memorial Gymnasium in memory of the 17 Purdue University football players, coaches, alumni, and fans who died in the Purdue Wreck railroad accident of 1903.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The structure was renovated in 1985 to house the computer science department.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 2006, it was renamed in honor of retired Provost Felix Haas and began to also house the Statistics department.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] East of the Memorial Mall is the Purdue Memorial Union, Purdue's student union building, and the adjacent Union Club Hotel.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] University Hall is the only building remaining from the original six-building campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Construction began in 1871, when the building was known as "The Main Building".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] University Hall originally housed the office of the president, a chapel, and classrooms.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] At the request of John Purdue, he was buried in the Memorial Mall, directly across from the main entrance of University Hall.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The area south of Mitch Daniels Boulevard is home to Purdue's agricultural, fine arts, life sciences, and veterinary buildings.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] This area also includes the Krannert School of Management, Horticulture Gardens, Discovery Park, Lyles Porter Hall and the Purdue Airport.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Lyles Porter Hall houses interdisciplinary healthcare facilities and classroom space within the College of Health and Human Sciences as well as the West Lafayette branch of the Indiana University School of Medicine.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The western portion of campus consists of student housing, dining, and recreation facilities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Córdova Recreational Sports Center, built in 1957, is the first building in the nation created solely to serve university student recreational needs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Much of the northern part of campus sits on land purchased for the university by industrialist David E.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Ross and author George Ade in the 1920s.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Many of Purdue's athletic facilities are there, including Ross–Ade Stadium (American football), Mackey Arena (basketball), and Lambert Fieldhouse (indoor track and field).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] This area also includes the Slayter Center of Performing Arts and Cary Quadrangle, one of the largest all-male housing units in the country.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University is ranked 43rd in the annual ranking of 2024 U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] News & World Report* categorizes Purdue University-West Lafayette as "more selective".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Of those accepted, 10,157 enrolled, a yield rate (the percentage of accepted students who choose to attend the university) of 24.9%.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's freshman retention rate is 92%, with 81.5% going on to graduate within six years.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university started test-optional admissions with the Fall 2021 incoming class in response to the COVID-19 pandemic and has extended this through Fall 2023.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Of the 62% of the incoming freshman class who submitted SAT scores; the middle 50 percent Composite scores were 1190–1430.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Of the 31% of enrolled freshmen in 2021 who submitted ACT scores; the middle 50 percent Composite score was between 26 and 33.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University is a college-sponsor of the National Merit Scholarship Program and sponsored 88 Merit Scholarship awards in 2020.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In the 2020–2021 academic year, 127 freshman students were National Merit Scholars.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue offers both undergraduate and graduate programs in over 211 major areas of study, and is well known for its competitive engineering curricula.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university has also been integral in America's history of aviation, having established the first college credit offered in flight training; the first four-year bachelor's degree in aviation; and the first university airport: Purdue University Airport.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's aviation technology and aeronautical engineering programs remain among the most competitive aviation-specific programs in the world.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In the mid-20th century, Purdue's aviation program expanded to encompass advanced spaceflight technology, giving rise to Purdue's nicknames *Cradle of Astronauts* and *Mother of Astronauts*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Twenty-seven Purdue graduates have become astronauts, including Gus Grissom, one of the original Mercury Seven astronauts; Neil Armstrong, who was the first person to walk on the Moon; and Eugene Cernan, who was the last person to walk on the Moon.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The English department at Purdue launched the first Online Writing Lab (OWL), in 1994.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Many colleges and universities use the Purdue OWL website as an academic writing reference source for proper word usage, punctuation, grammar, and style.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Professors criticized the partnership, begun in 2020, between OWL and the company Chegg, which provides AI-generated "homework help" that some consider to be plagiarism.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue is organized into 10 colleges and schools.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university's College of Agriculture supports the university's charge as a land-grant university for the study of agriculture throughout the state.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The College of Education offers undergraduate degrees in elementary education, social studies education, science education and special education, and graduate degrees in these and many other specialty areas of education.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue University College of Engineering was established in 1874 with programs in Civil and Mechanical Engineering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The college now offers BS, MS, and PhD degrees in more than a dozen disciplines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's engineering program has also educated 27 American astronauts, including Neil Armstrong and Eugene Cernan, who were the first and last astronauts to have walked on the Moon, respectively, and Gus Grissom, a member of the Mercury Seven.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 2025, the department announced an all-Boilermaker team to crew a commercial spaceflight mission flown by Virgin Galactic.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Many of Purdue's engineering disciplines are recognized as top-ten programs in the U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The college as a whole is currently ranked 4th in the U.S. of all doctorate-granting engineering schools by *U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university's Exploratory Studies program supports undergraduate students who enter the university without having a declared major.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It was founded as a pilot program in 1995 and made a permanent program in 1999.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The College of Health and Human Sciences was established in 2010 and is the newest college.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It offers BS, MS and PhD degrees in all 9 of its academic units.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's College of Liberal Arts contains the arts, social sciences and humanities programs at the university.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Liberal arts courses have been taught at Purdue since its founding in 1874.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The School of Science, Education, and Humanities was formed in 1953.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 1963, the School of Humanities, Social Sciences, and Education was established, although Bachelor of Arts degrees had begun to be conferred as early as 1959.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 1989, the School of Liberal Arts was created to encompass Purdue's arts, humanities, and social sciences programs, while education programs were split off into the newly formed School of Education.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The School of Liberal Arts was renamed the College of Liberal Arts in 2005.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Daniels School of Business offers management courses and programs at the undergraduate, master's, and doctoral levels.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university's College of Pharmacy was established in 1884 and is the 3rd oldest state-funded school of pharmacy in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Polytechnic Institute, formerly known as the College of Technology, offers bachelor's, master's and PhD degrees in a wide range of technology-related disciplines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] With over 30,000 living alumni, it is one of the largest technology schools in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In addition to the main school in West Lafayette, Purdue Polytechnic operates nine satellite campuses in Anderson, Columbus, Indianapolis, Kokomo, Lafayette, New Albany, Richmond, Vincennes, and South Bend.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] These locations offer certificate, associate, and/or bachelor's degrees, some of which are ABET-accredited technical degrees.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Polytechnic Institute also maintains three high school campuses (two in Indianapolis and one in South Bend) that focus on science, technology, engineering, and mathematics and feature hands-on project-based learning.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university's College of Science houses the university's science departments: Biological Sciences; Chemistry; Computer Science; Earth, Atmospheric, & Planetary Sciences; Mathematics; Physics & Astronomy; and Statistics.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The science courses offered by the college account for about one-fourth of Purdue's one million student credit hours.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The College of Veterinary Medicine is accredited by the AVMA.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's John Martinson Honors College supports an honors program for undergraduate students at the university.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Honors College's mission is to "create and foster well-rounded, well-educated global leaders," through their four pillars of interdisciplinary academics, undergraduate research, community and global engagement, and leadership development.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university expended $622.814 million in support of research system-wide in 2017, using funds received from the state and federal governments, industry, foundations, and individual donors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The faculty and more than 400 research laboratories put Purdue University among the leading research institutions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University is considered by the Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education to have "very high research activity".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue also was rated the nation's fourth best place to work in academia, according to rankings released in November 2007 by *The Scientist* magazine.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's researchers provide insight, knowledge, assistance, and solutions in many crucial areas.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] These include, but are not limited to Agriculture; Business and Economy; Education; Engineering; Environment; Healthcare; Individuals, Society, Culture; Manufacturing; Science; Technology; Veterinary Medicine.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Global Trade Analysis Project (GTAP), a global research consortium focused on global economic governance challenges (trade, climate, resource use) is also coordinated by the university.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University generated a record $438 million in sponsored research funding during the 2009–10 fiscal year with participation from National Science Foundation, National Aeronautics and Space Administration, and the U.S. departments of Agriculture, Defense, Energy, and Health and Human Services.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University was ranked fourth in Engineering research expenditures amongst all the colleges in the United States in 2017, with a research expenditure budget of 244.8 million.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University established the Discovery Park to bring innovation through multidisciplinary action.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In all of the eleven centers of Discovery Park, ranging from entrepreneurship to energy and advanced manufacturing, research projects reflect a large economic impact and address global challenges.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University's nanotechnology research program, built around the new Birck Nanotechnology Center in Discovery Park, ranks among the best in the nation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Research Park which opened in 1961 was developed by Purdue Research Foundation which is a private, nonprofit foundation created to assist Purdue.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The park is focused on companies operating in the arenas of life sciences, homeland security, engineering, advanced manufacturing and information technology.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It provides an interactive environment for experienced Purdue researchers and for private business and high-tech industry.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It currently employs more than 3,000 people in 155 companies, including 90 technology-based firms.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Research Park was ranked first by the Association of University Research Parks in 2004.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's library system consists of fifteen locations throughout the campus, including an archives and special collections research center, an undergraduate library, and several subject-specific libraries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] More than three million volumes, including one million electronic books, are held at these locations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Library houses the Amelia Earhart Collection, a collection of notes and letters belonging to Earhart and her husband George Putnam along with records related to her disappearance and subsequent search efforts.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] An administrative unit of Purdue University Libraries, Purdue University Press publishes books in the areas of agriculture, health, and engineering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's Sustainability Council, composed of university administrators and professors, meets monthly to discuss environmental issues and sustainability initiatives at Purdue.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The university's first LEED Certified building was an addition to the Mechanical Engineering Building, which was completed in Fall 2011.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The school is also in the process of developing an arboretum on campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In addition, a system has been set up to display live data detailing current energy production at the campus utility plant.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The school holds an annual "Green Week" each fall, an effort to engage the Purdue community with issues relating to environmental sustainability.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University is well-regarded for the strength of its STEM programs and has strong employer reputations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] News & World Report* ranked Purdue University the 7th most innovative national university, 8th best engineering school, 6th best school for internships and co-ops, 11th best for innovation, and 19th best public university in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In its 2026 edition, the *Times Higher Education* ranked Purdue University 10th among all global universities for Interdisciplinary Science (7th among universities in the United States).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It also ranked Purdue 30th among all global universities for engineering (16th among universities in the United States).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] As of April 2025, CSRankings.org ranked Purdue's computer science program 13th overall in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 2012, 8,562 students from 126 countries around the world attended Purdue University.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] For international student enrollment, Purdue ranks ninth among 4,500-plus public and private institutions and ranks fourth among all U.S. public universities, based on the 2024 Open Doors Report.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In 2012–13, 19,689 out of a total of 39,256 students enrolled were Indiana residents.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] As of 2013, the racial diversity of the US-resident undergraduate student body was 5.7% Asian, 4.4% Hispanic or Latino, and 4.0% black or African American.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Of the undergraduate students, 42.6% were female.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Domestic minorities constitute a total of 10.8% in the graduate student body population of which 37.3% are female.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Twenty-two percent of the student body is international, representing 126 countries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In graduate and professional student population, non-Indiana residents occupy an overwhelming majority, about 75%.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Almost all undergraduates and about 70% of the graduate student population attend full-time.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The school's selectivity for admissions is "more selective" by USNWR: approximately 49% of applicants are admitted.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] About one-third of the single undergraduate students on the West Lafayette campus live in university-owned buildings.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The rest live in fraternities, sororities, cooperatives, or private off-campus housing.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] School sources claim over 10,000 spaces available in seventeen separate residence halls for students on campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University hosts one of the nation's largest Greek communities, with roughly 40 fraternities and 30 sororities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Students at Purdue participate in more than 1,000 student organizations that cover a variety of interests.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Several campus-wide programs are planned by the Purdue Alumni Student Experience (part of the Alumni Association), Purdue Student Union Board, Purdue Student Government (PSG), or the Purdue Graduate Student Government (PGSG).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] PSG and PGSG are made up of representatives from each of the university's academic colleges and give recommendations to the faculty, administration, and sometimes to the state legislature.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Annual campus events include Boiler Gold Rush, Purdue University Dance Marathon, Spring Fest, and Grand Prix.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Boiler Gold Rush (BGR) is Purdue's annual student orientation program and a sports pep rally.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue University Dance Marathon (PUDM) is an 18-hour no-sitting, no-sleeping, dance marathon; over 2,000 students participate and the event raises over $1 million annually for Riley Hospital for Children in Indianapolis.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Spring Fest is an annual carnival with entertaining exhibits from many academic departments.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] A highlight of the weekend is the Entomology Department's Bug Bowl, where the sport of cricket spitting was invented in 1997.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Grand Prix, a 50-mile, 160-lap go-kart race ends Gala Week each year.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] All 33 participating karts are made from scratch by student teams.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The event has been raising money for student scholarships since it began in 1958.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue has a number of religious organizations on and near the campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Thomas Aquinas Catholic Church serves the Catholic community at Purdue and the surrounding community.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] There is also a non-denominational Christian church, Campus House, which is affiliated with the popular coffee-shop Greyhouse Coffee.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Hillel Foundation and Chabad at Purdue are the university's Jewish campus organizations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Islamic Society of Greater Lafayette has an Islamic center serving the needs of the Muslim community on campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The *Purdue Exponent*, an independent student newspaper, has the largest circulation of any Indiana college newspaper, with a daily circulation of 17,500 copies during the spring and fall semesters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] From 1889 to 2008 Purdue published a yearbook called the *Debris*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] WBAA are radio station operations owned by and licensed to Metropolitan Indianapolis Public Media, with studios at the university, featuring three noncommercial stations: WBAA News, WBAA Classical, and WBAA Jazz.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The stations can be heard on AM 920, 101.3 FM, and 105.9 FM.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] WBAA also broadcasts on HD Radio and digital platforms including wbaa.org and the WBAA app.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Elliott Hall of Music on the Purdue campus, and the transmitters are in Lafayette, Indiana.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] WBAA is the longest continuously operating radio station in Indiana, having been licensed on April 4, 1922.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Despite some public disapproval, in 2022, Purdue sold WBAA (AM) and WBAA-FM to WFYI-FM.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue received $700,000 in underwriting credit while agreeing to provide an investment of $250,000 annually for two years to WFYI to offset initial operating costs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Historically, there were three main campus radio stations at Purdue University which operated from residence halls: WCCR from Cary Quadrangle, WILY from Wiley Residence Hall, and WHHR from Harrison Residence Hall.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] No student radio stations currently broadcast on AM or FM frequencies and instead broadcast exclusively online.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The second iteration of WHHR operated from around 2008 until sometime in either 2011 or 2012, when it again ceased operations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] As of 2026, there have been one or two short-lived attempts to revive the station, but the studio remains empty and unused.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In the early 1990s, WILY also had a lapse in funding and closed operations until sometime in the 2000s, when student interest generated funds and resurrected the station.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Students are able to reserve time on WILY (now colloquially known among students as Wiley Radio) and broadcast on their service through analog equipment (such as vinyl records or actual instruments) or digital music streaming.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Podcasts are also commonplace and the facilities encourage them.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] WCCR and WILY both operate digitally 24/7 and are fully staffed by students, with each station's respective website detailing program schedules.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] W9YB is the callsign of the Amateur Radio Club at Purdue University.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] W9YB is the longest standing club on campus and also holds the self-declared title of having one of the largest and most active collegiate amateur radio stations in the country.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] W9YB actively participates in emergency management for the Tippecanoe County area and maintains ready status with its members in skills to assist.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] W9YB is among the longest standing amateur radio clubs in the United States, with the current callsign dating back to 1932 and the previous callsign 9YB dating back to 1920.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The *Movie Tribute Show* was created in a small television studio (now known as the Erik Mygrant Studio) on campus in 1999.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] On October 26, 1891, a newspaper in Crawfordsville, Indiana called Purdue's football team the "Boiler Makers" when writing about their trouncing of Wabash College.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Lafayette newspapers soon picked up the name, and in October 1892, *The Purdue Exponent*, Purdue's student newspaper, gave it the stamp of approval.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] In the early days of Purdue football, the team was called other names as well, including "haymakers", "railsplitters", "sluggers", and "cornfield sailors".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] This heritage is reflected in Purdue's official mascot: the Boilermaker Special (a truck-like vehicle that resembles a locomotive) and the athletic mascot Purdue Pete (a muscular hammer-wielding boilermaker).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The school colors of old gold and black were selected by Purdue's first football team in 1887 to resemble the orange and black of Princeton's then-successful team.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] This made Purdue football the first sports team to ever use a black and gold color palette.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The best known fight song is "Hail Purdue!".
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue has one of the few college athletic programs not funded by student fees or subsidized by the university.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] It is home to 18 Division I/I-A NCAA teams including football, basketball, cross country, tennis, wrestling, golf, volleyball, ice hockey (ACHA), and others.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue is a founding member of the Big Ten Conference, and played a central role in its creation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Traditional rivals include Big Ten colleagues the Indiana Hoosiers (see Indiana–Purdue rivalry), the Illinois Fighting Illini, and the Notre Dame Fighting Irish from the Atlantic Coast Conference (football program independent, however).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue's baseball facility was named in honor of two alumni, Anna Margaret Ross Alexander and her husband, John Arthur Alexander, when the new stadium was dedicated in 2013.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Boilermaker football team represents Purdue University in the NCAA Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue plays its home games at Ross-Ade Stadium on the university's campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Boilermakers compete in the Big Ten Conference as a member of the West Division.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Found on a farm in southern Indiana, the Old Oaken Bucket is one of the oldest American football trophies.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The winner of Purdue's annual game against the Indiana University Hoosiers gets to keep the trophy until the next face-off and add a bronze "P" or "I" link to its chain.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The first competition in 1925 led to a 0–0 tie, resulting in the first link on the chain being an "IP." As of 13 January 2024, Purdue led the series 77–42–6.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] During "Breakfast Club", best described as a cross between a pep rally and a Halloween party, students and even some alumni dress up in costumes, from traditional Halloween garb to creative hand-made costumes, as they bar-hop before Boilermaker home football games.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Breakfast Club plays a significant role during the football season and is informally a part of Purdue tradition.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Many Boilermaker fans are dedicated; getting up at 5:00 a.m. on Saturdays and lining up at the bars on Chauncey Hill and the levee by 6:00 a.m. on game days.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Breakfast Club tradition began in the 1980s during the annual Purdue Grand Prix race in April.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Another tradition is Saturday morning wake-ups, where the Boilermaker Special uses its many loud horns and whistles to wake dorm students up in preparation for the day's game.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team competes in NCAA Division I and is a member of the Big Ten Conference.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue won its 25th Big Ten Conference Championship and 2nd Big Ten Tournament Championship in 2023.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] This leads the conference, as Indiana University Bloomington is second with 22 conference championships.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue men's team has sent more than 30 players to the NBA including two overall No.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Purdue women's basketball team were the 1999 NCAA Champions and 2001 runners-up.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] The Boilermakers men's and women's basketball teams have won more Big Ten Championships than any other conference school, with 32 regular-season conference titles and 11 Big Ten Tournament titles.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p01] Purdue men's basketball achieved an all-time winning record against all Big Ten schools when it gained a winning record over Ohio State with three wins in 2023, improving that record from 91–92 to 94–92.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] The original faculty of six in 1874 has grown to 2,563 tenured and tenure-track faculty in the Purdue Statewide System by Fall 2007 totals.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] The number of faculty and staff members system-wide is 18,872.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] The current faculty includes scholars such as Arden L.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] (director of the National Science Foundation), R.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Graham Cooks, Douglas Comer, Louis de Branges de Bourcia (who proved the Bieberbach conjecture), Victor Raskin, David Sanders, Leah Jamieson, James L.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Mohler (who has written several manuals of computer graphics), and Samuel S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Purdue's tenured faculty comprises 60 academic deans, associate deans, and assistant deans; 63 academic department heads; 753 professors; 547 associate professors; and 447 assistant professors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Purdue employs 892 non-tenure-track faculty, lecturers, and postdoctoral researchers at its West Lafayette campus.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Purdue employs another 691 tenured and 1,021 non-tenure track faculty, lecturers, and postdoctoral researchers at its regional campuses and Statewide Technology unit.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Two faculty members (chemists Herbert C.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Brown and Ei-ichi Negishi) have been awarded Nobel Prizes while at Purdue.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] In all, 13 Nobel Prizes in five fields have been associated with Purdue, including students, researchers, and current and previous faculty.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Touloukian, founder of the Thermophysical Properties Research Center.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Purdue alumni have achieved recognition in a range of areas, particularly in the science, engineering, and aviation industries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] The university's alumni pool collectively holds over 15,000 United States patents.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Purdue alumni include 27 astronauts, including Gus Grissom, America's second man in space and first to fly in NASA's Gemini program, Neil Armstrong, the first to walk on the Moon, and Eugene Cernan, the last astronaut to do so.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Over one-third of all of NASA's crewed space missions have had at least one Purdue graduate as a crew member.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] In science, Purdue has also produced Nobel Prize–winning physicists in Edward Mills Purcell (BS) and Ben Roy Mottelson (BS), as well as Nobel Prize–winning chemist Akira Suzuki (post-doc).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Other noted Purdue alumni in science include pioneer of robotics and remote control technology Thomas B.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Sheridan; Debian founder Ian Murdock; Chinese physicist Deng Jiaxian, a founding father and key contributor to the Chinese nuclear weapon programs; mathematician Yitang Zhang; chemist Lawrence Rocks; biochemist Edwin T.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Olembo, a geneticist and environmentalist who went on to become the deputy executive director of UNEP and a UN Assistant Secretary-General, and who was recognized by Purdue in 1994 with a Distinguished Alumni Award for Agriculture.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] In business and economics, Purdue alumni include Stephen Bechtel, Jr., owner of Bechtel Corporation; Federal Reserve Bank president Jeffrey Lacker; and popcorn specialist Orville Redenbacher.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] In 2010, Bloomberg also revealed Purdue was one of the universities in America with the most undergraduate alumni serving as chief executive officers of S&P 500 firms.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] In government and culture, Purdue alumni include Pulitzer Prize–winners Booth Tarkington and John T.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Miller, former U.S. deputy secretary of education; and Hugo F.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Sonnenschein, former University of Chicago president.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Klemm, former CEO of Food Warming Equipment and Illinois state legislator, also graduated from Purdue.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Purdue has three NFL Super Bowl–winning quarterbacks in Drew Brees, Bob Griese, and Len Dawson.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Nineteen Purdue alumni had been on a Super Bowl–winning team as of 2011.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Purdue also produced Super Bowl IV winning coach Hank Stram.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] 2008 Daytona 500 winner Ryan Newman graduated from Purdue with a bachelor's degree in vehicle structure engineering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] Three Purdue alumni have received the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the highest civilian award of the United States: Neil Armstrong, Brian Lamb, and John Wooden.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] The 67,000-square-foot (6,200 m2) Dauch Alumni Center houses the Purdue for Life Foundation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/purdue-university-p02] The foundation was created in 2020 by uniting the Purdue Alumni Association and the University Development Office.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Soft elements, such as personnel, integrity, confidence, organizational culture, motivation, team spirit, and quality relationships.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Inspection is a major component of quality control, where physical product is examined visually (or the end results of a service are analyzed).
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Product inspectors will be provided with lists and descriptions of unacceptable product defects such as cracks or surface blemishes for example.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Early stone tools such as anvils had no holes and were not designed as interchangeable parts.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Mass production established processes for the creation of parts and system with identical dimensions and design, but these processes are not uniform and hence some customers were unsatisfied with the result.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Quality control separates the act of testing products to uncover defects from the decision to allow or deny product release, which may be determined by fiscal constraints.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] For contract work, particularly work awarded by government agencies, quality control issues are among the top reasons for not renewing a contract.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] The simplest form of quality control was a sketch of the desired item.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] If the item did not match the sketch, the item was rejected, in a simple Go/no go procedure.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] However, manufacturers soon found it was difficult and costly to make parts be exactly like their depiction; hence around 1840 tolerance limits were introduced, wherein a design would function if its parts were measured to be within the limits.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Quality was thus precisely defined using devices such as plug gauges and ring gauges.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] However, this did not address the problem of defective items; recycling or disposing of the waste adds to the cost of production, as does trying to reduce the defect rate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] Various methods have been proposed to prioritize quality control issues and determine whether to leave them unaddressed or use quality assurance techniques to improve and stabilize production.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] In project management, quality control requires the project manager and/or the project team to inspect the accomplished work to ensure its alignment with the project scope.
[src:american-national-standards-institute-nanotechnology-panel/quality-standards] In practice, projects typically have a dedicated quality control team which focuses on this area.
